[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] This value is known as the $\epsilon$ -outage capacity.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] In a fast-fading channel, where the latency requirement is greater than the coherence time and the codeword length spans many coherence periods, one can average over many independent channel fades by coding over a large number of coherence time intervals.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] Thus, it is possible to achieve a reliable rate of communication of $\mathbb {E} (\log _{2}(1+|h|^{2}SNR))$ [bits/s/Hz] and it is meaningful to speak of this value as the capacity of the fast-fading channel.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] Feedback capacity is the greatest rate at which information can be reliably transmitted, per unit time, over a point-to-point communication channel in which the receiver feeds back the channel outputs to the transmitter.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] Information-theoretic analysis of communication systems that incorporate feedback is more complicated and challenging than without feedback.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] Shannon chose feedback as the subject of the first Shannon Lecture, delivered at the 1973 IEEE International Symposium on Information Theory in Ashkelon, Israel.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] The feedback capacity is characterized by the maximum of the directed information between the channel inputs and the channel outputs, where the maximization is with respect to the causal conditioning of the input given the output.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] The directed information was coined by James Massey in 1990, who showed that its an upper bound on feedback capacity.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] For memoryless channels, Shannon showed that feedback does not increase the capacity, and the feedback capacity coincides with the channel capacity characterized by the mutual information between the input and the output.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] The feedback capacity is known as a closed-form expression only for several examples such as the trapdoor channel, Ising channel,.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] For some other channels, it is characterized through constant-size optimization problems such as the binary erasure channel with a no-consecutive-ones input constraint, NOST channel.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] That is, for each time i there exists a feedback of the previous output $Y_{i-1}$ such that the encoder has access to all previous outputs $Y^{i-1}$ .
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] An $(2^{nR},n)$ code is a pair of encoding and decoding mappings with ${\mathcal {W}}=[1,2,\dots ,2^{nR}]$ , and W is uniformly distributed.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] A rate R is said to be **achievable** if there exists a sequence of codes $(2^{nR},n)$ such that the *average probability of error:* $P_{e}^{(n)}\triangleq \Pr({\hat {W}}\neq W)$ tends to zero as $n\to \infty$ .
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] The **feedback capacity** is denoted by $C_{\text{feedback}}$ , and is defined as the supremum over all achievable rates.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] When the Gaussian noise is colored, the channel has memory.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] Consider for instance the simple case on an autoregressive model noise process $z_{i}=z_{i-1}+w_{i}$ where $w_{i}\sim N(0,1)$ is an i.i.d. process.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] The feedback capacity is difficult to solve in the general case.
[src:information-theory/channel-capacity] There are some techniques that are related to control theory and Markov decision processes if the channel is discrete.
[src:information-theory/checksum] A **checksum** is a small-sized block of data derived from another block of digital data for the purpose of detecting errors that may have been introduced during its transmission or storage.
[src:information-theory/checksum] By themselves, checksums are often used to verify data integrity but are not relied upon to verify data authenticity.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The procedure which generates this checksum is called a **checksum function** or **checksum algorithm**.
[src:information-theory/checksum] Depending on its design goals, a good checksum algorithm usually outputs a significantly different value, even for small changes made to the input.
[src:information-theory/checksum] Checksum functions are related to hash functions, fingerprints, randomization functions, and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:information-theory/checksum] However, each of those concepts has different applications and therefore different design goals.
[src:information-theory/checksum] For instance, a function returning the start of a string can provide a hash appropriate for some applications but will never be a suitable checksum.
[src:information-theory/checksum] Checksums are used as cryptographic primitives in larger authentication algorithms.
[src:information-theory/checksum] For cryptographic systems with these two specific design goals, see HMAC.
[src:information-theory/checksum] Check digits and parity bits are special cases of checksums, appropriate for small blocks of data (such as Social Security numbers, bank account numbers, computer words, single bytes, etc.).
[src:information-theory/checksum] Some error-correcting codes are based on special checksums which not only detect common errors but also allow the original data to be recovered in certain cases.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The simplest checksum algorithm is the so-called longitudinal parity check, which breaks the data into "words" with a fixed number *n* of bits, and then computes the bitwise exclusive or (XOR) of all those words.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The result is appended to the message as an extra word.
[src:information-theory/checksum] In simpler terms, for *n*=1 this means adding a bit to the end of the data bits to guarantee that there is an even number of '1's.
[src:information-theory/checksum] To check the integrity of a message, the receiver computes the bitwise exclusive or of all its words, including the checksum; if the result is not a word consisting of *n* zeros, the receiver knows a transmission error occurred.
[src:information-theory/checksum] With this checksum, any transmission error which flips a single bit of the message, or an odd number of bits, will be detected as an incorrect checksum.
[src:information-theory/checksum] However, an error that affects two bits will not be detected if those bits lie at the same position in two distinct words.
[src:information-theory/checksum] Also swapping of two or more words will not be detected.
[src:information-theory/checksum] If the affected bits are independently chosen at random, the probability of a two-bit error being undetected is 1/*n*.
[src:information-theory/checksum] A variant of the previous algorithm is to add all the "words" as unsigned binary numbers, discarding any overflow bits, and append the two's complement of the total as the checksum.
[src:information-theory/checksum] To validate a message, the receiver adds all the words in the same manner, including the checksum; if the result is not a word full of zeros, an error must have occurred.
[src:information-theory/checksum] This variant, too, detects any single-bit error, but the pro modular sum is used in SAE J1708.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The simple checksums described above fail to detect some common errors which affect many bits at once, such as changing the order of data words, or inserting or deleting words with all bits set to zero.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The checksum algorithms most used in practice, such as Fletcher's checksum, Adler-32, and cyclic redundancy checks (CRCs), address these weaknesses by considering not only the value of each word but also its position in the sequence.
[src:information-theory/checksum] This feature generally increases the cost of computing the checksum.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The idea of fuzzy checksum was developed for detection of email spam by building up cooperative databases from multiple ISPs of email suspected to be spam.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The content of such spam may often vary in its details, which would render normal checksumming ineffective.
[src:information-theory/checksum] By contrast, a "fuzzy checksum" reduces the body text to its characteristic minimum, then generates a checksum in the usual manner.
[src:information-theory/checksum] This greatly increases the chances of slightly different spam emails producing the same checksum.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The ISP spam detection software, such as SpamAssassin, of co-operating ISPs, submits checksums of all emails to the centralised service such as DCC.
[src:information-theory/checksum] If the count of a submitted fuzzy checksum exceeds a certain threshold, the database notes that this probably indicates spam.
[src:information-theory/checksum] ISP service users similarly generate a fuzzy checksum on each of their emails and request the service for a spam likelihood.
[src:information-theory/checksum] A message that is *m* bits long can be viewed as a corner of the *m*-dimensional hypercube.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The effect of a checksum algorithm that yields an *n*-bit checksum is to map each *m*-bit message to a corner of a larger hypercube, with dimension *m* + *n*.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The 2*m* + *n* corners of this hypercube represent all possible received messages.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The valid received messages (those that have the correct checksum) comprise a smaller set, with only 2*m* corners.
[src:information-theory/checksum] A single-bit transmission error then corresponds to a displacement from a valid corner (the correct message and checksum) to one of the *m* adjacent corners.
[src:information-theory/checksum] An error which affects *k* bits moves the message to a corner which is *k* steps removed from its correct corner.
[src:information-theory/checksum] The goal of a good checksum algorithm is to spread the valid corners as far from each other as possible, to increase the likelihood "typical" transmission errors will end up in an invalid corner.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] A **cyclic redundancy check** (**CRC**) is an error-detecting code commonly used in digital networks and storage devices to detect accidental changes to digital data.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Blocks of data entering these systems get a short *check value* attached, based on the remainder of a polynomial division of their contents.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] On retrieval, the calculation is repeated and, in the event the check values do not match, corrective action can be taken against data corruption.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] CRCs can be used for error correction (see bitfilters).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] CRCs are so called because the *check* (data verification) value is a *redundancy* (it expands the message without adding information) and the algorithm is based on *cyclic* codes.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] CRCs are popular because they are simple to implement in binary hardware, easy to analyze mathematically, and particularly good at detecting common errors caused by noise in transmission channels.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Because the check value has a fixed length, the function that generates it is occasionally used as a hash function.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] CRCs are based on the theory of cyclic error-correcting codes.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The use of systematic cyclic codes, which encode messages by adding a fixed-length check value, for the purpose of error detection in communication networks, was first proposed by W.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Cyclic codes are not only simple to implement but have the benefit of being particularly well suited for the detection of burst errors: contiguous sequences of erroneous data symbols in messages.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] This is important because burst errors are common transmission errors in many communication channels, including magnetic and optical storage devices.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Typically an *n*-bit CRC applied to a data block of arbitrary length will detect any single error burst not longer than *n* bits, and the fraction of all longer error bursts that it will detect is approximately (1 − 2−*n*).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Specification of a CRC code requires definition of a so-called generator polynomial.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] This polynomial becomes the divisor in a polynomial long division, which takes the message as the dividend and in which the quotient is discarded and the remainder becomes the result.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The important caveat is that the polynomial coefficients are calculated according to the arithmetic of a finite field, so the addition operation can always be performed bitwise-parallel (there is no carry between digits).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] In practice, all commonly used CRCs employ the finite field of two elements, GF(2).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The two elements are usually called 0 and 1, comfortably matching computer architecture.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] A CRC is called an *n*-bit CRC when its check value is *n* bits long.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] For a given *n*, multiple CRCs are possible, each with a different polynomial.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Such a polynomial has highest degree *n*, which means it has *n* + 1 terms.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] In other words, the polynomial has a length of *n* + 1; its encoding requires *n* + 1 bits.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Note that most polynomial specifications either drop the MSb or LSb, since they are always 1.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The CRC and associated polynomial typically have a name of the form CRC-*n*-XXX as in the table below.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The simplest error-detection system, the parity bit, is in fact a 1-bit CRC: it uses the generator polynomial *x* + 1 (two terms), and has the name CRC-1.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] A CRC-enabled device calculates a short, fixed-length binary sequence, known as the *check value* or *CRC*, for each block of data to be sent or stored and appends it to the data, forming a *codeword*.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] When a codeword is received or read, the device either compares its check value with one freshly calculated from the data block, or equivalently, performs a CRC on the whole codeword and compares the resulting check value with an expected *residue* constant.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] If the CRC values do not match, then the block contains a data error.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The device may take corrective action, such as rereading the block or requesting that it be sent again.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Otherwise, the data is assumed to be error-free (though, with some small probability, it may contain undetected errors; this is inherent in the nature of error-checking).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] CRCs are specifically designed to protect against common types of errors on communication channels, where they can provide quick and reasonable assurance of the integrity of messages delivered.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] However, they are not suitable for protecting against intentional alteration of data.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Firstly, as there is no authentication, an attacker can edit a message and recompute the CRC without the substitution being detected.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] When stored alongside the data, CRCs and cryptographic hash functions by themselves do not protect against *intentional* modification of data.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Any application that requires protection against such attacks must use cryptographic authentication mechanisms, such as message authentication codes or digital signatures (which are commonly based on cryptographic hash functions).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Secondly, unlike cryptographic hash functions, CRC is an easily reversible function, which makes it unsuitable for use in digital signatures.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] where c depends on the length of x and y .
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] To compute an *n*-bit binary CRC, line the bits representing the input in a row, and position the (*n* + 1)-bit pattern representing the CRC's divisor (called a "polynomial") underneath the left end of the row.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] In this example, we shall encode 14 bits of message with a 3-bit CRC, with a polynomial *x*3 + *x* + 1.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The polynomial is written in binary as the coefficients; a 3rd-degree polynomial has 4 coefficients (1*x*3 + 0*x*2 + 1*x* + 1).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] In this case, the coefficients are 1, 0, 1 and 1.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The result of the calculation is 3 bits long, which is why it is called a 3-bit CRC.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] However, 4 bits are needed to explicitly state the polynomial.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] This is first padded with zeros corresponding to the bit length *n* of the CRC.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] This is done so that the resulting code word is in systematic form.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The algorithm acts on the bits directly above the divisor in each step.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The result for that iteration is the bitwise XOR of the polynomial divisor with the bits above it.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The bits not above the divisor are simply copied directly below for that step.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The divisor is then shifted right to align with the highest remaining 1 bit in the input, and the process is repeated until the divisor reaches the right-hand end of the input row.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Since the leftmost divisor bit zeroed every input bit it touched, when this process ends the only bits in the input row that can be nonzero are the n bits at the right-hand end of the row.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] These *n* bits are the remainder of the division step, and will also be the value of the CRC function (unless the chosen CRC specification calls for some postprocessing).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The validity of a received message can easily be verified by performing the above calculation again, this time with the check value added instead of zeroes.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The remainder should equal zero if there are no detectable errors.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The following Python code outlines a function which will return the initial CRC remainder for a chosen input and polynomial, with either 1 or 0 as the initial padding.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Mathematical analysis of this division-like process reveals how to select a divisor that guarantees good error-detection properties.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] In this analysis, the digits of the bit strings are taken as the coefficients of a polynomial in some variable *x*—coefficients that are elements of the finite field GF(2) (the integers modulo 2, i.e. either a zero or a one), instead of more familiar numbers.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The set of binary polynomials is a mathematical ring.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The selection of the generator polynomial is the most important part of implementing the CRC algorithm.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The polynomial must be chosen to maximize the error-detecting capabilities while minimizing overall collision probabilities.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The most important attribute of the polynomial is its length (largest degree(exponent) +1 of any one term in the polynomial), because of its direct influence on the length of the computed check value.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The most commonly used polynomial lengths are 9 bits (CRC-8), 17 bits (CRC-16), 33 bits (CRC-32), and 65 bits (CRC-64).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] A CRC is called an *n*-bit CRC when its check value is *n*-bits.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Such a polynomial has highest degree *n*, and hence *n* + 1 terms (the polynomial has a length of *n* + 1).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The CRC has a name of the form CRC-*n*-XXX.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The design of the CRC polynomial depends on the maximum total length of the block to be protected (data + CRC bits), the desired error protection features, and the type of resources for implementing the CRC, as well as the desired performance.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] A common misconception is that the "best" CRC polynomials are derived from either irreducible polynomials or irreducible polynomials times the factor 1 + *x*, which adds to the code the ability to detect all errors affecting an odd number of bits.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] In reality, all the factors described above should enter into the selection of the polynomial and may lead to a reducible polynomial.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] However, choosing a reducible polynomial will result in a certain proportion of missed errors, due to the quotient ring having zero divisors.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] If r is the degree of the primitive generator polynomial, then the maximal total block length is $2^{r}-1$ , and the associated code is able to detect any single-bit or double-bit errors.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] However, if we use the generator polynomial $g(x)=p(x)(1+x)$ , where p is a primitive polynomial of degree $r-1$ , then the maximal total block length is $2^{r-1}-1$ , and the code is able to detect single, double, triple and any odd number of errors.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] A polynomial $g(x)$ that admits other factorizations may be chosen then so as to balance the maximal total blocklength with a desired error detection power.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The BCH codes are a powerful class of such polynomials.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Regardless of the reducibility properties of a generator polynomial of degree *r*, if it includes the "+1" term, the code will be able to detect error patterns that are confined to a window of *r* contiguous bits.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] These patterns are called "error bursts".
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The concept of the CRC as an error-detecting code gets complicated when an implementer or standards committee uses it to design a practical system.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] These complications mean that there are three common ways to express a polynomial as an integer: the first two, which are mirror images in binary, are the constants found in code; the third is the number found in Koopman's papers.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] CRCs in proprietary protocols might be obfuscated by using a non-trivial initial value and a final XOR, but these techniques do not introduce cryptographic strength into the algorithm and can be reverse engineered using straightforward methods.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Numerous varieties of cyclic redundancy checks have been incorporated into technical standards.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] By no means does one algorithm, or one of each degree, suit every purpose; Koopman and Chakravarty recommend selecting a polynomial according to the application requirements and the expected distribution of message lengths.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The number of distinct CRCs in use has confused developers, a situation which authors have sought to address.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] There are three polynomials reported for CRC-12, twenty-two conflicting definitions of CRC-16, and seven of CRC-32.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The polynomials commonly applied are not the most efficient ones possible.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] In particular, iSCSI and SCTP have adopted one of the findings of this research, the CRC-32C (Castagnoli) polynomial.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The earliest known appearances of the 32-bit polynomial were in their 1975 publications: Technical Report 2956 by Brayer for Mitre, published in January and released for public dissemination through DTIC in August, and Hammond, Brown and Liu's report for the Rome Laboratory, published in May.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Both reports contained contributions from the other team.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] During December 1975, Brayer and Hammond presented their work in a paper at the IEEE National Telecommunications Conference: the IEEE CRC-32 polynomial is the generating polynomial of a Hamming code and was selected for its error detection performance.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Even so, the Castagnoli CRC-32C polynomial used in iSCSI or SCTP matches its performance on messages from 58 bits to 131 kbits, and outperforms it in several size ranges including the two most common sizes of Internet packet.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The ITU-T G.hn standard also uses CRC-32C to detect errors in the payload (although it uses CRC-16-CCITT for PHY headers).
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] CRC-32C computation is implemented in hardware as an operation (`CRC32`) of SSE4.2 instruction set, first introduced in Intel processors' Nehalem microarchitecture.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] ARM AArch64 architecture also provides hardware acceleration for both CRC-32 and CRC-32C operations.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The table below lists only the polynomials of the various algorithms in use.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Variations of a particular protocol can impose pre-inversion, post-inversion and reversed bit ordering as described above.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] For example, the CRC-32 used in Gzip and Bzip2 use the same polynomial, but Gzip employs reversed bit ordering, while Bzip2 does not.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Note that even parity polynomials in GF(2) with degree greater than 1 are never primitive.
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] Even parity polynomial marked as primitive in this table represent a primitive polynomial multiplied by $\left(x+1\right)$ .
[src:information-theory/cyclic-redundancy-check] The most significant bit of a polynomial is always 1, and is not shown in the hex representations.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] In information theory, the **entropy** of a random variable quantifies the average level of uncertainty or information associated with the variable's potential states or possible outcomes.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] This measures the expected amount of information needed to describe the state of the variable, considering the distribution of probabilities across all potential states.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The choice of base for log {\displaystyle \log } ({\displaystyle \log }), the logarithm, varies for different applications.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Base 2 gives the unit of bits (or "shannons"), while base *e* gives "natural units" nat, and base 10 gives units of "dits", "bans", or "hartleys".
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] An equivalent definition of entropy is the expected value of the self-information of a variable.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The concept of information entropy was introduced by Claude Shannon in his 1948 paper "A Mathematical Theory of Communication", and is also referred to as **Shannon entropy**.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon's theory defines a data communication system composed of three elements: a source of data, a communication channel, and a receiver.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The "fundamental problem of communication" – as expressed by Shannon – is for the receiver to be able to identify what data was generated by the source, based on the signal it receives through the channel.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon considered various ways to encode, compress, and transmit messages from a data source, and proved in his source coding theorem that the entropy represents an absolute mathematical limit on how well data from the source can be losslessly compressed onto a perfectly noiseless channel.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon strengthened this result considerably for noisy channels in his noisy-channel coding theorem.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Entropy in information theory is directly analogous to the entropy in statistical thermodynamics.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The analogy results when the values of the random variable designate energies of microstates, so Gibbs's formula for the entropy is formally identical to Shannon's formula.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Entropy has relevance to other areas of mathematics such as combinatorics and machine learning.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The definition can be derived from a set of axioms establishing that entropy should be a measure of how informative the average outcome of a variable is.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] For a continuous random variable, differential entropy is analogous to entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The definition E [ − log ⁡ p ( X ) ] {\displaystyle \mathbb {E} [-\log p(X)]} ({\displaystyle \mathbb {E} [-\log p(X)]}) generalizes the above.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The core idea of information theory is that the "informational value" of a communicated message depends on the degree to which the content of the message is surprising.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] If a highly likely event occurs, the message carries very little information.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] On the other hand, if a highly unlikely event occurs, the message is much more informative.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] For instance, the knowledge that some particular number *will not* be the winning number of a lottery provides very little information, because any particular chosen number will almost certainly not win.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] However, knowledge that a particular number *will* win a lottery has high informational value because it communicates the occurrence of a very low probability event.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The *information content,* also called the *surprisal* or *self-information,* of an event E {\displaystyle E} ({\displaystyle E}) is a function that increases as the probability p ( E ) {\displaystyle p(E)} ({\displaystyle p(E)}) of an event decreases.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] When p ( E ) {\displaystyle p(E)} ({\displaystyle p(E)}) is close to 1, the surprisal of the event is low, but if p ( E ) {\displaystyle p(E)} ({\displaystyle p(E)}) is close to 0, the surprisal of the event is high.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] In fact, log is the only function that satisfies a specific set of conditions defined in section *§ Characterization*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Entropy measures the expected (i.e., average) amount of information conveyed by identifying the outcome of a random trial.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] This implies that rolling a die has higher entropy than tossing a coin because each outcome of a single die roll has smaller probability ( p = 1 / 6 {\displaystyle p=1/6} ({\displaystyle p=1/6})) than each outcome of a coin toss ( p = 1 / 2 {\displaystyle p=1/2} ({\displaystyle p=1/2})).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Consider a coin with probability *p* of landing on heads and probability 1 − *p* of landing on tails.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The maximum surprise is when *p* = 1/2, for which one outcome is not expected over the other.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] In this case a coin flip has an entropy of one bit (similarly, one trit with equiprobable values contains log 2 ⁡ 3 {\displaystyle \log _{2}3} ({\displaystyle \log _{2}3}) (about 1.58496) bits of information because it can have one of three values).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The minimum surprise is when *p* = 0 (impossibility) or *p* = 1 (certainty) and the entropy is zero bits.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] When the entropy is zero, there is no uncertainty at all – no freedom of choice – no information.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Other values of *p* give entropies between zero and one bits.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Information theory is useful to calculate the smallest amount of information required to convey a message, as in data compression.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] For example, consider the transmission of sequences comprising the 4 characters 'A', 'B', 'C', and 'D' over a binary channel.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] If all 4 letters are equally likely (25%), one cannot do better than using two bits to encode each letter.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] However, if the probabilities of each letter are unequal, say 'A' occurs with 70% probability, 'B' with 26%, and 'C' and 'D' with 2% each, one could assign variable length codes.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] With this representation, 70% of the time only one bit needs to be sent, 26% of the time two bits, and only 4% of the time 3 bits.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] On average, fewer than 2 bits are required since the entropy is lower (owing to the high prevalence of 'A' followed by 'B' – together 96% of characters).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The calculation of the sum of probability-weighted log probabilities measures and captures this effect.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] English text, treated as a string of characters, has fairly low entropy; i.e. it is fairly predictable.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] We can be fairly certain that, for example, 'e' will be far more common than 'z', that the combination 'qu' will be much more common than any other combination with a 'q' in it, and that the combination 'th' will be more common than 'z', 'q', or 'qu'.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] After the first few letters one can often guess the rest of the word.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] English text has between 0.6 and 1.3 bits of entropy per character of the message.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Here E {\displaystyle \mathbb {E} } ({\displaystyle \mathbb {E} }) is the expected value operator, and I is the information content of *X*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] I ⁡ ( X ) {\displaystyle \operatorname {I} (X)} ({\displaystyle \operatorname {I} (X)}) is itself a random variable.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The entropy can explicitly be written as: H ( X ) = − ∑ x ∈ X p ( x ) log b ⁡ p ( x ) , {\displaystyle \mathrm {H} (X)=-\sum _{x\in {\mathcal {X}}}p(x)\log _{b}p(x),} ({\displaystyle \mathrm {H} (X)=-\sum _{x\in {\mathcal {X}}}p(x)\log _{b}p(x),}) where *b* is the base of the logarithm used.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Common values of *b* are 2, Euler's number *e*, and 10, and the corresponding units of entropy are the bits for *b* = 2, nats for *b* = *e*, and bans for *b* = 10.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] This quantity should be understood as the remaining randomness in the random variable X {\displaystyle X} ({\displaystyle X}) given the random variable Y {\displaystyle Y} ({\displaystyle Y}).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Entropy can be formally defined in the language of measure theory as follows: Let ( X , Σ , μ ) {\displaystyle (X,\Sigma ,\mu )} ({\displaystyle (X,\Sigma ,\mu )}) be a probability space.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Let A ∈ Σ {\displaystyle A\in \Sigma } ({\displaystyle A\in \Sigma }) be an event.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Let M {\displaystyle M} ({\displaystyle M}) be a sigma-algebra on X {\displaystyle X} ({\displaystyle X}).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Consider tossing a coin with known, not necessarily fair, probabilities of coming up heads or tails; this can be modeled as a Bernoulli process.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The entropy of the unknown result of the next toss of the coin is maximized if the coin is fair (that is, if heads and tails both have equal probability 1/2).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] This is the situation of maximum uncertainty as it is most difficult to predict the outcome of the next toss; the result of each toss of the coin delivers one full bit of information.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] However, if we know the coin is not fair, but comes up heads or tails with probabilities *p* and *q*, where *p* ≠ *q*, then there is less uncertainty.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Every time it is tossed, one side is more likely to come up than the other.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The reduced uncertainty is quantified in a lower entropy: on average each toss of the coin delivers less than one full bit of information.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Uniform probability yields maximum uncertainty and therefore maximum entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Entropy, then, can only decrease from the value associated with uniform probability.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The extreme case is that of a double-headed coin that never comes up tails, or a double-tailed coin that never results in a head.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The entropy is zero: each toss of the coin delivers no new information as the outcome of each coin toss is always certain.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] To understand the meaning of −Σ *p**i* log(*p**i*), first define an information function I in terms of an event *i* with probability *p**i*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] I(1) = 0: events that always occur do not communicate information.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] I(*p*1·*p*2) = I(*p*1) + I(*p*2): the information learned from independent events is the sum of the information learned from each event.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] I(*p*) is a twice continuously differentiable function of p.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Given two independent events, if the first event can yield one of *n* equiprobable outcomes and another has one of *m* equiprobable outcomes then there are *mn* equiprobable outcomes of the joint event.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] This means that if log2(*n*) bits are needed to encode the first value and log2(*m*) to encode the second, one needs log2(*mn*) = log2(*m*) + log2(*n*) to encode both.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] In fact, the only possible values of I {\displaystyle \operatorname {I} } ({\displaystyle \operatorname {I} }) are I ⁡ ( u ) = k log ⁡ u {\displaystyle \operatorname {I} (u)=k\log u} ({\displaystyle \operatorname {I} (u)=k\log u}) for k < 0 {\displaystyle k<0} ({\displaystyle k<0}).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Additionally, choosing a value for *k* is equivalent to choosing a value x > 1 {\displaystyle x>1} ({\displaystyle x>1}) for k = − 1 / log ⁡ x {\displaystyle k=-1/\log x} ({\displaystyle k=-1/\log x}), so that *x* corresponds to the base for the logarithm.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Thus, entropy is characterized by the above four properties.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The different units of information (bits for the binary logarithm log2, nats for the natural logarithm ln, bans for the decimal logarithm log10 and so on) are constant multiples of each other.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] For instance, in case of a fair coin toss, heads provides log2(2) = 1 bit of information, which is approximately 0.693 nats or 0.301 decimal digits.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Because of additivity, *n* tosses provide *n* bits of information, which is approximately 0.693*n* nats or 0.301*n* decimal digits.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The *meaning* of the events observed (the meaning of *messages*) does not matter in the definition of entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Entropy only takes into account the probability of observing a specific event, so the information it encapsulates is information about the underlying probability distribution, not the meaning of the events themselves.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Another characterization of entropy uses the following properties.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Symmetry: H should be unchanged if the outcomes *x**i* are re-ordered.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Maximum: H n {\displaystyle \mathrm {H} _{n}} ({\displaystyle \mathrm {H} _{n}}) should be maximal if all the outcomes are equally likely i.e.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Increasing number of outcomes: for equiprobable events, the entropy should increase with the number of outcomes i.e.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Choosing *k* = *n*, *b*1 = ... = *b**n* = 1 this implies that the entropy of a certain outcome is zero: Η1(1) = 0.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] This implies that the efficiency of a source set with *n* symbols can be defined simply as being equal to its *n*-ary entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] See also Redundancy (information theory).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The characterization here imposes an additive property with respect to a partition of a set.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Meanwhile, the conditional probability is defined in terms of a multiplicative property, P ( A ∣ B ) ⋅ P ( B ) = P ( A ∩ B ) {\displaystyle P(A\mid B)\cdot P(B)=P(A\cap B)} ({\displaystyle P(A\mid B)\cdot P(B)=P(A\cap B)}).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Observe that a logarithm mediates between these two operations.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The conditional entropy and related quantities inherit simple relation, in turn.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The measure theoretic definition in the previous section defined the entropy as a sum over expected surprisals μ ( A ) ⋅ ln ⁡ μ ( A ) {\displaystyle \mu (A)\cdot \ln \mu (A)} ({\displaystyle \mu (A)\cdot \ln \mu (A)}) for an extremal partition.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Here the logarithm is ad hoc and the entropy is not a measure in itself.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] At least in the information theory of a binary string, log 2 {\displaystyle \log _{2}} ({\displaystyle \log _{2}}) lends itself to practical interpretations.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Motivated by such relations, a plethora of related and competing quantities have been defined.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] For example, David Ellerman's analysis of a "logic of partitions" defines a competing measure in structures dual to that of subsets of a universal set.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Information is quantified as "dits" (distinctions), a measure on partitions.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] "Dits" can be converted into Shannon's bits, to get the formulas for conditional entropy, and so on.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Additivity: H ( X , Y ) = H ( X ) + H ( Y ) {\displaystyle \mathrm {H} (X,Y)=\mathrm {H} (X)+\mathrm {H} (Y)} ({\displaystyle \mathrm {H} (X,Y)=\mathrm {H} (X)+\mathrm {H} (Y)}) when the random variables X , Y {\displaystyle X,Y} ({\displaystyle X,Y}) are independent.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] It was shown that any function H {\displaystyle \mathrm {H} } ({\displaystyle \mathrm {H} }) satisfying the above properties must be a constant multiple of Shannon entropy, with a non-negative constant.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] It is worth noting that if we drop the "small for small probabilities" property, then H {\displaystyle \mathrm {H} } ({\displaystyle \mathrm {H} }) must be a non-negative linear combination of the Shannon entropy and the Hartley entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The inspiration for adopting the word *entropy* in information theory came from the close resemblance between Shannon's formula and very similar known formulae from statistical mechanics.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Willard Gibbs in 1878 after earlier work by Ludwig Boltzmann (1872).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] At an everyday practical level, the links between information entropy and thermodynamic entropy are not evident.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Physicists and chemists are apt to be more interested in *changes* in entropy as a system spontaneously evolves away from its initial conditions, in accordance with the second law of thermodynamics, rather than an unchanging probability distribution.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] As the minuteness of the Boltzmann constant *k*B indicates, the changes in *S* / *k*B for even tiny amounts of substances in chemical and physical processes represent amounts of entropy that are extremely large compared to anything in data compression or signal processing.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] In classical thermodynamics, entropy is defined in terms of macroscopic measurements and makes no reference to any probability distribution, which is central to the definition of information entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] It is assumed that each microstate is equally likely, so that the probability of a given microstate is *p**i* = 1/*W*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] When these probabilities are substituted into the above expression for the Gibbs entropy (or equivalently *k*B times the Shannon entropy), Boltzmann's equation results.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] In information theoretic terms, the information entropy of a system is the amount of "missing" information needed to determine a microstate, given the macrostate.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Adding heat to a system increases its thermodynamic entropy because it increases the number of possible microscopic states of the system that are consistent with the measurable values of its macroscopic variables, making any complete state description longer.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] (See article: *maximum entropy thermodynamics*).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Landauer's principle imposes a lower bound on the amount of heat a computer must generate to process a given amount of information, though modern computers are far less efficient.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon's definition of entropy, when applied to an information source, can determine the minimum channel capacity required to reliably transmit the source as encoded binary digits.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon's entropy measures the information contained in a message as opposed to the portion of the message that is determined (or predictable).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Examples of the latter include redundancy in language structure or statistical properties relating to the occurrence frequencies of letter or word pairs, triplets etc.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The minimum channel capacity can be realized in theory by using the typical set or in practice using Huffman, Lempel–Ziv or arithmetic coding.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] (See also Kolmogorov complexity.) In practice, compression algorithms deliberately include some judicious redundancy in the form of checksums to protect against errors.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The entropy rate of a data source is the average number of bits per symbol needed to encode it.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon's experiments with human predictors show an information rate between 0.6 and 1.3 bits per character in English; the PPM compression algorithm can achieve a compression ratio of 1.5 bits per character in English text.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] If a compression scheme is lossless – one in which you can always recover the entire original message by decompression – then a compressed message has the same quantity of information as the original but is communicated in fewer characters.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] It has more information (higher entropy) per character.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] A compressed message has less redundancy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon's source coding theorem states a lossless compression scheme cannot compress messages, on average, to have *more* than one bit of information per bit of message, but that any value *less* than one bit of information per bit of message can be attained by employing a suitable coding scheme.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The entropy of a message per bit multiplied by the length of that message is a measure of how much total information the message contains.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon's theorem also implies that no lossless compression scheme can shorten *all* messages.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] If some messages come out shorter, at least one must come out longer due to the pigeonhole principle.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] A 2011 study in *Science* estimates the world's technological capacity to store and communicate optimally compressed information normalized on the most effective compression algorithms available in the year 2007, therefore estimating the entropy of the technologically available sources.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The authors estimate humankind technological capacity to store information (fully entropically compressed) in 1986 and again in 2007.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] They break the information into three categories—to store information on a medium, to receive information through one-way broadcast networks, or to exchange information through two-way telecommunications networks.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Entropy is one of several ways to measure biodiversity and is applied in the form of the Shannon index.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] A diversity index is a quantitative statistical measure of how many different types exist in a dataset, such as species in a community, accounting for ecological richness, evenness, and dominance.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Specifically, Shannon entropy is the logarithm of 1D, the true diversity index with parameter equal to 1.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The Shannon index is related to the proportional abundances of types.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] It is important not to confuse the above concepts.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Often it is only clear from context which one is meant.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] For example, when someone says that the "entropy" of the English language is about 1 bit per character, they are actually modeling the English language as a stochastic process and talking about its entropy *rate*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Shannon himself used the term in this way.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] If very large blocks are used, the estimate of per-character entropy rate may become artificially low because the probability distribution of the sequence is not known exactly; it is only an estimate.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] As a practical code, this corresponds to assigning each book a unique identifier and using it in place of the text of the book whenever one wants to refer to the book.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The key idea is that the complexity of the probabilistic model must be considered.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Kolmogorov complexity is a theoretical generalization of this idea that allows the consideration of the information content of a sequence independent of any particular probability model; it considers the shortest program for a universal computer that outputs the sequence.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] A code that achieves the entropy rate of a sequence for a given model, plus the codebook (i.e. the probabilistic model), is one such program, but it may not be the shortest.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] The Fibonacci sequence is 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, .... treating the sequence as a message and each number as a symbol, there are almost as many symbols as there are characters in the message, giving an entropy of approximately log2(*n*).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] In cryptanalysis, entropy is often roughly used as a measure of the unpredictability of a cryptographic key, though its real uncertainty is unmeasurable.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] For example, a 128-bit key that is uniformly and randomly generated has 128 bits of entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] It also takes (on average) 2 127 {\displaystyle 2^{127}} ({\displaystyle 2^{127}}) guesses to break by brute force.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Entropy fails to capture the number of guesses required if the possible keys are not chosen uniformly.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Instead, a measure called *guesswork* can be used to measure the effort required for a brute force attack.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] Other problems may arise from non-uniform distributions used in cryptography.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] For example, a 1,000,000-digit binary one-time pad using exclusive or.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] If the pad has 1,000,000 bits of entropy, it is perfect.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] If the pad has 999,999 bits of entropy, evenly distributed (each individual bit of the pad having 0.999999 bits of entropy) it may provide good security.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] But if the pad has 999,999 bits of entropy, where the first bit is fixed and the remaining 999,999 bits are perfectly random, the first bit of the ciphertext will not be encrypted at all.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] A common way to define entropy for text is based on the Markov model of text.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p01] where *i* is a **state** (certain preceding characters) and p i ( j ) {\displaystyle p_{i}(j)} ({\displaystyle p_{i}(j)}) is the probability of *j* given *i* as the previous character.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] A source set X {\displaystyle {\mathcal {X}}} ({\displaystyle {\mathcal {X}}}) with a non-uniform distribution will have less entropy than the same set with a uniform distribution (i.e. the "optimized alphabet").
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Efficiency has utility in quantifying the effective use of a communication channel.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] This formulation is also referred to as the normalized entropy, as the entropy is divided by the maximum entropy log b ⁡ ( n ) {\displaystyle {\log _{b}(n)}} ({\displaystyle {\log _{b}(n)}}).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Furthermore, the efficiency is indifferent to the choice of (positive) base *b*, as indicated by the insensitivity within the final logarithm above thereto.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] The Shannon entropy is restricted to random variables taking discrete values.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] This is the differential entropy (or continuous entropy).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] A precursor of the continuous entropy *h*[*f*] is the expression for the functional *Η* in the H-theorem of Boltzmann.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Although the analogy between both functions is suggestive, the following question must be set: is the differential entropy a valid extension of the Shannon discrete entropy?
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Differential entropy lacks a number of properties that the Shannon discrete entropy has – it can even be negative – and corrections have been suggested, notably limiting density of discrete points.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] In order to obtain a generally finite measure as the bin size goes to zero.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] In the discrete case, the bin size is the (implicit) width of each of the *n* (finite or infinite) bins whose probabilities are denoted by *p**n*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] As the continuous domain is generalized, the width must be made explicit.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] To do this, start with a continuous function *f* discretized into bins of size Δ {\displaystyle \Delta } ({\displaystyle \Delta }).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] which is, as said before, referred to as the differential entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] This means that the differential entropy *is not* a limit of the Shannon entropy for *n* → ∞.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Rather, it differs from the limit of the Shannon entropy by an infinite offset (see also the article on information dimension).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] It turns out as a result that, unlike the Shannon entropy, the differential entropy is *not* in general a good measure of uncertainty or information.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] For example, the differential entropy can be negative; also it is not invariant under continuous co-ordinate transformations.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] This problem may be illustrated by a change of units when *x* is a dimensioned variable.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] *f*(*x*) will then have the units of 1/*x*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] The argument of the logarithm must be dimensionless, otherwise it is improper, so that the differential entropy as given above will be improper.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] If *Δ* is some "standard" value of *x* (i.e.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] In fact, the limit of discrete entropy as N → ∞ {\displaystyle N\rightarrow \infty } ({\displaystyle N\rightarrow \infty }) would also include a term of log ⁡ ( N ) {\displaystyle \log(N)} ({\displaystyle \log(N)}), which would in general be infinite.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] This is expected: continuous variables would typically have infinite entropy when discretized.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] The limiting density of discrete points is really a measure of how much easier a distribution is to describe than a distribution that is uniform over its quantization scheme.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Another useful measure of entropy that works equally well in the discrete and the continuous case is the **relative entropy** of a distribution.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] It is defined as the Kullback–Leibler divergence from the distribution to a reference measure *m* as follows.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] In this form the relative entropy generalizes (up to change in sign) both the discrete entropy, where the measure *m* is the counting measure, and the differential entropy, where the measure *m* is the Lebesgue measure.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] If the measure *m* is itself a probability distribution, the relative entropy is non-negative, and zero if *p* = *m* as measures.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] It is defined for any measure space, hence coordinate independent and invariant under co-ordinate reparameterizations if one properly takes into account the transformation of the measure *m*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] The relative entropy, and (implicitly) entropy and differential entropy, do depend on the "reference" measure *m*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Terence Tao used entropy to make a useful connection trying to solve the Erdős discrepancy problem.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] And in an interval [n, n+H] the sum over that interval could become arbitrarily large.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] For example, a sequence of +1's (which are values of *X**H* could take) have trivially low entropy and their sum would become big.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] But the key insight was showing a reduction in entropy by non negligible amounts as one expands H leading inturn to unbounded growth of a mathematical object over this random variable is equivalent to showing the unbounded growth per the Erdős discrepancy problem.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] The proof is quite involved and it brought together breakthroughs not just in novel use of Shannon entropy, but also it used the Liouville function along with averages of modulated multiplicative functions in short intervals.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Proving it also broke the "parity barrier" for this specific problem.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] While the use of Shannon entropy in the proof is novel it is likely to open new research in this direction.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Entropy has become a useful quantity in combinatorics.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] We sketch how Loomis–Whitney follows from this: Indeed, let *X* be a uniformly distributed random variable with values in *A* and so that each point in *A* occurs with equal probability.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Then (by the further properties of entropy mentioned above) Η(*X*) = log|*A*|, where |*A*| denotes the cardinality of *A*.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Now use this to bound the right side of Shearer's inequality and exponentiate the opposite sides of the resulting inequality you obtain.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] A nice interpretation of this is that the number of binary strings of length *n* with exactly *k* many 1's is approximately 2 n H ( k / n ) {\displaystyle 2^{n\mathrm {H} (k/n)}} ({\displaystyle 2^{n\mathrm {H} (k/n)}}).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Machine learning techniques arise largely from statistics and also information theory.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] In general, entropy is a measure of uncertainty and the objective of machine learning is to minimize uncertainty.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Decision tree learning algorithms use relative entropy to determine the decision rules that govern the data at each node.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] The information gain is used to identify which attributes of the dataset provide the most information and should be used to split the nodes of the tree optimally.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Bayesian inference models often apply the principle of maximum entropy to obtain prior probability distributions.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] The idea is that the distribution that best represents the current state of knowledge of a system is the one with the largest entropy, and is therefore suitable to be the prior.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] Classification in machine learning performed by logistic regression or artificial neural networks often employs a standard loss function, called cross-entropy loss, that minimizes the average cross entropy between ground truth and predicted distributions.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory-p02] In general, cross entropy is a measure of the differences between two datasets similar to the KL divergence (also known as relative entropy).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] The choice of base for $\log$ , the logarithm, varies for different applications.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] The definition $\mathbb {E} [-\log p(X)]$ generalizes the above.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] The *information content,* also called the *surprisal* or *self-information,* of an event E is a function that increases as the probability $p(E)$ of an event decreases.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] When $p(E)$ is close to 1, the surprisal of the event is low, but if $p(E)$ is close to 0, the surprisal of the event is high.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] This relationship is described by the function $\log \left({\frac {1}{p(E)}}\right),$ where $\log$ is the logarithm, which gives 0 surprise when the probability of the event is 1.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] This implies that rolling a die has higher entropy than tossing a coin because each outcome of a single die roll has smaller probability ( $p=1/6$ ) than each outcome of a coin toss ( $p=1/2$ ).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] In this case a coin flip has an entropy of one bit (similarly, one trit with equiprobable values contains $\log _{2}3$ (about 1.58496) bits of information because it can have one of three values).
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] Here $\mathbb {E}$ is the expected value operator, and I is the information content of *X*. $\operatorname {I} (X)$ is itself a random variable.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] The entropy can explicitly be written as: $\mathrm {H} (X)=-\sum _{x\in {\mathcal {X}}}p(x)\log _{b}p(x),$ where *b* is the base of the logarithm used.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] This quantity should be understood as the remaining randomness in the random variable X given the random variable Y .
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] Entropy can be formally defined in the language of measure theory as follows: Let $(X,\Sigma ,\mu )$ be a probability space.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] A $\mu$ -almost partition is a set family $P\subseteq {\mathcal {P}}(X)$ such that $\mu (\bigcup P)=1$ and $\mu (A\cap B)=0$ for all distinct $A,B\in P$ .
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] The entropy of M is $\mathrm {H} _{\mu }(M)=\sup _{P\subseteq M}\mathrm {H} _{\mu }(P).$ Finally, the entropy of the probability space is $\mathrm {H} _{\mu }(\Sigma )$ , that is, the entropy with respect to $\mu$ of the sigma-algebra of *all* measurable subsets of X .
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] In fact, the only possible values of $\operatorname {I}$ are $\operatorname {I} (u)=k\log u$ for $k<0$ .
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] Additionally, choosing a value for *k* is equivalent to choosing a value $x>1$ for $k=-1/\log x$ , so that *x* corresponds to the base for the logarithm.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] Meanwhile, the conditional probability is defined in terms of a multiplicative property, $P(A\mid B)\cdot P(B)=P(A\cap B)$ .
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] The measure theoretic definition in the previous section defined the entropy as a sum over expected surprisals $\mu (A)\cdot \ln \mu (A)$ for an extremal partition.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] At least in the information theory of a binary string, $\log _{2}$ lends itself to practical interpretations.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] Additivity: $\mathrm {H} (X,Y)=\mathrm {H} (X)+\mathrm {H} (Y)$ when the random variables $X,Y$ are independent.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] It was shown that any function $\mathrm {H}$ satisfying the above properties must be a constant multiple of Shannon entropy, with a non-negative constant.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] Compared to the previously mentioned characterizations of entropy, this characterization focuses on the properties of entropy as a function of random variables (subadditivity and additivity), rather than the properties of entropy as a function of the probability vector $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{n}$ .
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] It is worth noting that if we drop the "small for small probabilities" property, then $\mathrm {H}$ must be a non-negative linear combination of the Shannon entropy and the Hartley entropy.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] In statistical thermodynamics the most general formula for the thermodynamic entropy *S* of a thermodynamic system is the Gibbs entropy $S=-k_{\text{B}}\sum _{i}p_{i}\ln p_{i}\,,$ where *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, and *p**i* is the probability of a microstate.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] The Gibbs entropy translates over almost unchanged into the world of quantum physics to give the von Neumann entropy introduced by John von Neumann in 1927: $S=-k_{\text{B}}\,{\rm {Tr}}(\rho \ln \rho )\,,$ where ρ is the density matrix of the quantum mechanical system and Tr is the trace.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] It also takes (on average) $2^{127}$ guesses to break by brute force.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] where *i* is a **state** (certain preceding characters) and $p_{i}(j)$ is the probability of *j* given *i* as the previous character.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] A source set ${\mathcal {X}}$ with a non-uniform distribution will have less entropy than the same set with a uniform distribution (i.e. the "optimized alphabet").
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] This formulation is also referred to as the normalized entropy, as the entropy is divided by the maximum entropy ${\log _{b}(n)}$ .
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] To do this, start with a continuous function *f* discretized into bins of size $\Delta$ .
