[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] In fact, the limit of discrete entropy as $N\rightarrow \infty$ would also include a term of $\log(N)$ , which would in general be infinite.
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] A nice interpretation of this is that the number of binary strings of length *n* with exactly *k* many 1's is approximately $2^{n\mathrm {H} (k/n)}$ .
[src:information-theory/entropy-information-theory] The information gain in decision trees $IG(Y,X)$ , which is equal to the difference between the entropy of Y and the conditional entropy of Y given X , quantifies the expected information, or the reduction in entropy, from additionally knowing the value of an attribute X .
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] In information theory and coding theory with applications in computer science and telecommunications, **error detection and correction** (**EDAC**) or **error control** are techniques that enable reliable delivery of digital data over unreliable communication channels.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Many communication channels are subject to channel noise, and thus errors may be introduced during transmission from the source to a receiver.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Error detection techniques allow detecting such errors, while error correction enables reconstruction of the original data in many cases.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] In classical antiquity, copyists of the Hebrew Bible were paid for their work according to the number of stichs (lines of verse).
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] As the prose books of the Bible were hardly ever written in stichs, the copyists, in order to estimate the amount of work, had to count the letters.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] This also helped ensure accuracy in the transmission of the text with the production of subsequent copies.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Between the 7th and 10th centuries CE a group of Jewish scribes formalized and expanded this to create the Numerical Masorah to ensure accurate reproduction of the sacred text.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] It included counts of the number of words in a line, section, book and groups of books, noting the middle stich of a book, word use statistics, and commentary.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Standards became such that a deviation in even a single letter in a Torah scroll was considered unacceptable.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The effectiveness of their error correction method was verified by the accuracy of copying through the centuries demonstrated by discovery of the Dead Sea Scrolls in 1947–1956, dating from c.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The modern development of error correction codes is credited to Richard Hamming in 1947.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A description of Hamming's code appeared in Claude Shannon's *A Mathematical Theory of Communication* and was quickly generalized by Marcel J.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] All error-detection and correction schemes add some redundancy (i.e., some extra data) to a message, which receivers can use to check consistency of the delivered message and to recover data that has been determined to be corrupted.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Error detection and correction schemes can be either systematic or non-systematic.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] In a systematic scheme, the transmitter sends the original (error-free) data and attaches a fixed number of *check bits* (or *parity data*), which are derived from the data bits by some encoding algorithm.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] If error detection is required, a receiver can simply apply the same algorithm to the received data bits and compare its output with the received check bits; if the values do not match, an error has occurred at some point during the transmission.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] If error correction is required, a receiver can apply the decoding algorithm to the received data bits and the received check bits to recover the original error-free data.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] In a system that uses a non-systematic code, the original message is transformed into an encoded message carrying the same information, and that has at least as many bits as the original message.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Good error control performance requires the scheme to be selected based on the characteristics of the communication channel.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Common channel models include memoryless models where errors occur randomly and with a certain probability, and dynamic models where errors occur primarily in bursts.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Consequently, error-detecting and -correcting codes can be generally distinguished between *random-error-detecting/correcting* and *burst-error-detecting/correcting*.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Some codes can also be suitable for a mixture of random errors and burst errors.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] If the channel characteristics cannot be determined or are highly variable, an error-detection scheme may be combined with a system for retransmission of erroneous data.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] This is known as automatic repeat request (ARQ), and is most notably used on the Internet.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] An alternate approach for error control is hybrid automatic repeat request (HARQ), which is a combination of ARQ and error-correction coding.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Automatic repeat request (ARQ) is an error control method for data transmission that makes use of error-detection codes, acknowledgment and/or negative acknowledgment messages, and timeouts to achieve reliable data transmission.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] An *acknowledgment* is a message sent by the receiver to indicate that it has correctly received a data frame.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Usually, when the transmitter does not receive the acknowledgment before the timeout occurs (i.e., within a reasonable amount of time after sending the data frame), it retransmits the frame until it is either correctly received or the error persists beyond a predetermined number of retransmissions.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Three types of ARQ protocols are Stop-and-wait ARQ, Go-Back-N ARQ, and Selective Repeat ARQ.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] ARQ is appropriate if the communication channel has varying or unknown capacity, such as is the case on the Internet.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] However, ARQ requires the availability of a back channel, results in possibly increased latency due to retransmissions, and requires the maintenance of buffers and timers for retransmissions, which in the case of network congestion can put a strain on the server and overall network capacity.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] For example, ARQ is used on shortwave radio data links in the form of ARQ-E, or combined with multiplexing as ARQ-M.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Since the receiver does not have to ask the sender for retransmission of the data, a backchannel is not required in forward error correction.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Error-correcting codes are used in lower-layer communication such as cellular network, high-speed fiber-optic communication and Wi-Fi, as well as for reliable storage in media such as flash memory, hard disk and RAM.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Shannon's theorem is an important theorem in forward error correction, and describes the maximum information rate at which reliable communication is possible over a channel that has a certain error probability or signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] This strict upper limit is expressed in terms of the channel capacity.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] More specifically, the theorem says that there exist codes such that with increasing encoding length the probability of error on a discrete memoryless channel can be made arbitrarily small, provided that the code rate is lower than the channel capacity.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The code rate is defined as the fraction *k/n* of *k* source symbols and *n* encoded symbols.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The actual maximum code rate allowed depends on the error-correcting code used, and may be lower.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] This is because Shannon's proof was only of existential nature, and did not show how to construct codes that are both optimal and have efficient encoding and decoding algorithms.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Hybrid ARQ is a combination of ARQ and forward error correction.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The latter approach is particularly attractive on an erasure channel when using a rateless erasure code.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Error detection is most commonly realized using a suitable hash function (or specifically, a checksum, cyclic redundancy check or other algorithm).
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A hash function adds a fixed-length *tag* to a message, which enables receivers to verify the delivered message by recomputing the tag and comparing it with the one provided.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] There exists a vast variety of different hash function designs.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] However, some are of particularly widespread use because of either their simplicity or their suitability for detecting certain kinds of errors (e.g., the cyclic redundancy check's performance in detecting burst errors).
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A random-error-correcting code based on minimum distance coding can provide a strict guarantee on the number of detectable errors, but it may not protect against a preimage attack.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A repetition code is a coding scheme that repeats the bits across a channel to achieve error-free communication.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Given a stream of data to be transmitted, the data are divided into blocks of bits.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Each block is transmitted some predetermined number of times.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] For example, to send the bit pattern 1011, the four-bit block can be repeated three times, thus producing 1011 1011 1011.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] If this twelve-bit pattern was received as 1010 1011 1011 – where the first block is unlike the other two – an error has occurred.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A repetition code is very inefficient and can be susceptible to problems if the error occurs in exactly the same place for each group (e.g., 1010 1010 1010 in the previous example would be detected as correct).
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The advantage of repetition codes is that they are extremely simple, and are in fact used in some transmissions of numbers stations.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A *parity bit* is a bit that is added to a group of source bits to ensure that the number of set bits (i.e., bits with value 1) in the outcome is even or odd.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] It is a very simple scheme that can be used to detect single or any other odd number (i.e., three, five, etc.) of errors in the output.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] An even number of flipped bits will make the parity bit appear correct even though the data is erroneous.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Parity bits added to each *word* sent are called transverse redundancy checks, while those added at the end of a stream of *words* are called longitudinal redundancy checks.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] For example, if each of a series of m-bit *words* has a parity bit added, showing whether there were an odd or even number of ones in that word, any word with a single error in it will be detected.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] It will not be known where in the word the error is, however.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] If, in addition, after each stream of n words a parity sum is sent, each bit of which shows whether there were an odd or even number of ones at that bit-position sent in the most recent group, the exact position of the error can be determined and the error corrected.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] This method is only guaranteed to be effective, however, if there are no more than 1 error in every group of n words.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] With more error correction bits, more errors can be detected and, in some cases, corrected.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] There are also other bit-grouping techniques.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A *checksum* of a message is a modular arithmetic sum of message code words of a fixed word length (e.g., byte values).
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The sum may be negated by means of a ones'-complement operation prior to transmission to detect unintentional all-zero messages.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Checksum schemes include parity bits, check digits, and longitudinal redundancy checks.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Some checksum schemes, such as the Damm algorithm, the Luhn algorithm, and the Verhoeff algorithm, are specifically designed to detect errors commonly introduced by humans in writing down or remembering identification numbers.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A *cyclic redundancy check* (CRC) is a non-secure hash function designed to detect accidental changes to digital data in computer networks.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] It is not suitable for detecting maliciously introduced errors.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] It is characterized by specification of a *generator polynomial*, which is used as the divisor in a polynomial long division over a finite field, taking the input data as the dividend.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A CRC has properties that make it well suited for detecting burst errors.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] CRCs are particularly easy to implement in hardware and are therefore commonly used in computer networks and storage devices such as hard disk drives.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The parity bit can be seen as a special-case 1-bit CRC.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The output of a *cryptographic hash function*, also known as a *message digest*, can provide strong assurances about data integrity, whether changes of the data are accidental (e.g., due to transmission errors) or maliciously introduced.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Any modification to the data will likely be detected through a mismatching hash value.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Furthermore, given some hash value, it is typically infeasible to find some input data (other than the one given) that will yield the same hash value.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] If an attacker can change not only the message but also the hash value, then a *keyed hash* or message authentication code (MAC) can be used for additional security.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Without knowing the key, it is not possible for the attacker to easily or conveniently calculate the correct keyed hash value for a modified message.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Digital signatures can provide strong assurances about data integrity, whether the changes of the data are accidental or maliciously introduced.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Digital signatures are perhaps most notable for being part of the HTTPS protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Any error-correcting code can be used for error detection.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A code with *minimum Hamming distance*, *d*, can detect up to *d* − 1 errors in a code word.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Using minimum-distance-based error-correcting codes for error detection can be suitable if a strict limit on the minimum number of errors to be detected is desired.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Codes with minimum Hamming distance *d* = 2 are degenerate cases of error-correcting codes and can be used to detect single errors.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The parity bit is an example of a single-error-detecting code.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Applications that require low latency (such as telephone conversations) cannot use automatic repeat request (ARQ); they must use forward error correction (FEC).
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] By the time an ARQ system discovers an error and re-transmits it, the re-sent data will arrive too late to be usable.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Applications where the transmitter immediately forgets the information as soon as it is sent (such as most television cameras) cannot use ARQ; they must use FEC because when an error occurs, the original data is no longer available.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Applications that use ARQ must have a return channel; applications having no return channel cannot use ARQ.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Applications that require extremely low error rates (such as digital money transfers) must use ARQ due to the possibility of uncorrectable errors with FEC.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Reliability and inspection engineering also make use of the theory of error-correcting codes, as well as natural language.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The development of error-correction codes was tightly coupled with the history of deep-space missions due to the extreme dilution of signal power over interplanetary distances and the limited power availability aboard space probes.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Whereas early missions sent their data uncoded, starting in 1968, digital error correction was implemented in the form of (sub-optimally decoded) convolutional codes and Reed–Muller codes.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The Reed–Muller code was well suited to the noise the spacecraft was subject to (approximately matching a bell curve), and was implemented for the Mariner spacecraft and used on missions between 1969 and 1977.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The Voyager 1 and Voyager 2 missions, which started in 1977, were designed to deliver color imaging and scientific information from Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] This resulted in increased coding requirements, and thus, the spacecraft were supported by (optimally Viterbi-decoded) convolutional codes that could be concatenated with an outer Golay (24,12,8) code.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The Voyager 2 craft additionally supported an implementation of a Reed–Solomon code.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The concatenated Reed–Solomon–Viterbi (RSV) code allowed for very powerful error correction, and enabled the spacecraft's extended journey to Uranus and Neptune.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] After ECC system upgrades in 1989, both crafts used V2 RSV coding.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems currently recommends usage of error correction codes with performance similar to the Voyager 2 RSV code as a minimum.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Concatenated codes are increasingly falling out of favor with space missions, and are replaced by more powerful codes such as Turbo codes or LDPC codes.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The different kinds of deep space and orbital missions that are conducted suggest that trying to find a one-size-fits-all error correction system will be an ongoing problem.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] For missions close to Earth, the nature of the noise in the communication channel is different from that which a spacecraft on an interplanetary mission experiences.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Additionally, as a spacecraft increases its distance from Earth, the problem of correcting for noise becomes more difficult.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The demand for satellite transponder bandwidth continues to grow, fueled by the desire to deliver television (including new channels and high-definition television) and IP data.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Transponder availability and bandwidth constraints have limited this growth.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Transponder capacity is determined by the selected modulation scheme and the proportion of capacity consumed by FEC.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Error detection and correction codes are often used to improve the reliability of data storage media.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A parity track capable of detecting single-bit errors was present on the first magnetic tape data storage in 1951.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The optimal rectangular code used in group coded recording tapes not only detects but also corrects single-bit errors.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Some file formats, particularly archive formats, include a checksum (most often CRC-32]) to detect corruption and truncation and can employ redundancy or parity files to recover portions of corrupted data.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Reed-Solomon codes are used in compact discs to correct errors caused by scratches.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Modern hard drives use Reed–Solomon codes to detect and correct minor errors in sector reads, and to recover corrupted data from failing sectors and store that data in the spare sectors.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] RAID systems use a variety of error correction techniques to recover data when a hard drive completely fails.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Filesystems such as ZFS or Btrfs, as well as some RAID implementations, support data scrubbing and resilvering, which allows bad blocks to be detected and (hopefully) recovered before they are used.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] The recovered data may be re-written to exactly the same physical location, to spare blocks elsewhere on the same piece of hardware, or the data may be rewritten onto replacement hardware.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) may provide stronger protection against soft errors by relying on error-correcting codes.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Such error-correcting memory, known as *ECC* or *EDAC-protected* memory, is particularly desirable for mission-critical applications, such as scientific computing, financial, medical, etc. as well as extraterrestrial applications due to the increased radiation in space.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Error-correcting memory controllers traditionally use Hamming codes, although some use triple modular redundancy.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] Interleaving allows distributing the effect of a single cosmic ray potentially upsetting multiple physically neighboring bits across multiple words by associating neighboring bits to different words.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] As long as a single-event upset (SEU) does not exceed the error threshold (e.g., a single error) in any particular word between accesses, it can be corrected (e.g., by a single-bit error-correcting code), and the illusion of an error-free memory system may be maintained.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] In addition to hardware providing features required for ECC memory to operate, operating systems usually contain related reporting facilities that are used to provide notifications when soft errors are transparently recovered.
[src:information-theory/error-detection-and-correction] A few systems also support memory scrubbing to catch and correct errors early before they become unrecoverable.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In computer science and telecommunications, **Hamming codes** are a family of linear error-correcting codes.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hamming codes can detect one-bit and two-bit errors, or correct one-bit errors without detection of uncorrected errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] By contrast, the simple parity code cannot correct errors, and can detect only an odd number of bits in error.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hamming codes are perfect codes, that is, they achieve the highest possible rate for codes with their block length and minimum distance of three.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hamming invented Hamming codes in 1950 as a way of automatically correcting errors introduced by punched card readers.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In his original paper, Hamming elaborated his general idea, but specifically focused on the Hamming(7,4) code which adds three parity bits to four bits of data.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In mathematical terms, Hamming codes are a class of binary linear codes.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] For each integer *r* ≥ 2 there is a code-word with block length *n* = 2*r* − 1 and message length *k* = 2*r* − *r* − 1.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hence the rate of Hamming codes is *R* = *k* / *n* = 1 − *r* / (2*r* − 1), which is the highest possible for codes with minimum distance of three (i.e., the minimal number of bit changes needed to go from any code word to any other code word is three) and block length 2*r* − 1.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The parity-check matrix of a Hamming code is constructed by listing all columns of length *r* that are non-zero, which means that the dual code of the Hamming code is the shortened Hadamard code, also known as a Simplex code.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The parity-check matrix has the property that any two columns are pairwise linearly independent.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Due to the limited redundancy that Hamming codes add to the data, they can only detect and correct errors when the error rate is low.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] This is the case in computer memory (usually RAM), where bit errors are extremely rare and Hamming codes are widely used.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Memory with this correction system is known as ECC memory.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In this context, an extended Hamming code having one extra parity bit is often used.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Extended Hamming codes achieve a Hamming distance of four, which allows the decoder to distinguish between when at most one one-bit error occurs and when any two-bit errors occur.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In this sense, extended Hamming codes are single-error correcting and double-error detecting, abbreviated as **SECDED**.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Richard Hamming, the inventor of Hamming codes, worked at Bell Labs in the late 1940s on the Bell Model V computer, an electromechanical relay-based machine with cycle times in seconds.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Input was fed in on punched paper tape, seven-eighths of an inch wide, which had up to six holes per row.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] During weekdays, when errors in the relays were detected, the machine would stop and flash lights so that the operators could correct the problem.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] During after-hours periods and on weekends, when there were no operators, the machine simply moved on to the next job.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hamming worked on weekends, and grew increasingly frustrated with having to restart his programs from scratch due to detected errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In a taped interview, Hamming said, "And so I said, 'Damn it, if the machine can detect an error, why can't it locate the position of the error and correct it?'".
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Over the next few years, he worked on the problem of error-correction, developing an increasingly powerful array of algorithms.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In 1950, he published what is now known as Hamming code, which remains in use today in applications such as ECC memory.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] A number of simple error-detecting codes were used before Hamming codes, but none were as effective as Hamming codes in the same overhead of space.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Parity adds a single bit that indicates whether the number of ones (bit-positions with values of one) in the preceding data was even or odd.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If an odd number of bits is changed in transmission, the message will change parity and the error can be detected at this point; however, the bit that changed may have been the parity bit itself.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The most common convention is that a parity value of one indicates that there is an odd number of ones in the data, and a parity value of zero indicates that there is an even number of ones.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the number of bits changed is even, the check bit will be valid and the error will not be detected.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Moreover, parity does not indicate which bit contained the error, even when it can detect it.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The data must be discarded entirely and re-transmitted from scratch.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] On a noisy transmission medium, a successful transmission could take a long time or may never occur.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] However, while the quality of parity checking is poor, since it uses only a single bit, this method results in the least overhead.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] A two-out-of-five code is an encoding scheme which uses five bits consisting of exactly three 0s and two 1s.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] This provides ${\binom {5}{3}}=10$ possible combinations, enough to represent the digits 0–9.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] This scheme can detect all single bit-errors, all odd numbered bit-errors and some even numbered bit-errors (for example the flipping of both 1-bits).
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] However it still cannot correct any of these errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Another code in use at the time repeated every data bit multiple times in order to ensure that it was sent correctly.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] For instance, if the data bit to be sent is a 1, an *n* = 3 *repetition code* will send 111.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the three bits received are not identical, an error occurred during transmission.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the channel is clean enough, most of the time only one bit will change in each triple.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Therefore, 001, 010, and 100 each correspond to a 0 bit, while 110, 101, and 011 correspond to a 1 bit, with the greater quantity of digits that are the same ('0' or a '1') indicating what the data bit should be.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] A code with this ability to reconstruct the original message in the presence of errors is known as an *error-correcting* code.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] This triple repetition code is a Hamming code with *m* = 2, since there are two parity bits, and 22 − 2 − 1 = 1 data bit.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Such codes cannot correctly repair all errors, however.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In our example, if the channel flips two bits and the receiver gets 001, the system will detect the error, but conclude that the original bit is 0, which is incorrect.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If we increase the size of the bit string to four, we can detect all two-bit errors but cannot correct them (the quantity of parity bits is even); at five bits, we can both detect and correct all two-bit errors, but not all three-bit errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Moreover, increasing the size of the parity bit string is inefficient, reducing throughput by three times in our original case, and the efficiency drops drastically as we increase the number of times each bit is duplicated in order to detect and correct more errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If more error-correcting bits are included with a message, and if those bits can be arranged such that different incorrect bits produce different error results, then bad bits could be identified.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In a seven-bit message, there are seven possible single bit errors, so three error control bits could potentially specify not only that an error occurred but also which bit caused the error.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hamming studied the existing coding schemes, including two-of-five, and generalized their concepts.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] To start with, he developed a nomenclature to describe the system, including the number of data bits and error-correction bits in a block.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] For instance, parity includes a single bit for any data word, so assuming ASCII words with seven bits, Hamming described this as an *(8,7)* code, with eight bits in total, of which seven are data.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The repetition example would be *(3,1)*, following the same logic.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The code rate is the second number divided by the first, for our repetition example, 1/3.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hamming also noticed the problems with flipping two or more bits, and described this as the "distance" (it is now called the *Hamming distance*, after him).
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Parity has a distance of 2, so one bit flip can be detected but not corrected, and any two bit flips will be invisible.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The (3,1) repetition has a distance of 3, as three bits need to be flipped in the same triple to obtain another code word with no visible errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] It can correct one-bit errors or it can detect - but not correct - two-bit errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] A (4,1) repetition (each bit is repeated four times) has a distance of 4, so flipping three bits can be detected, but not corrected.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] When three bits flip in the same group there can be situations where attempting to correct will produce the wrong code word.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In general, a code with distance *k* can detect but not correct *k* − 1 errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hamming was interested in two problems at once: increasing the distance as much as possible, while at the same time increasing the code rate as much as possible.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] During the 1940s he developed several encoding schemes that were dramatic improvements on existing codes.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The key to all of his systems was to have the parity bits overlap, such that they managed to check each other as well as the data.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The following general algorithm generates a single-error correcting (SEC) code for any number of bits.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The main idea is to choose the error-correcting bits such that the index-XOR (the XOR of all the bit positions containing a 1) is 0.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] (in binary) as the error-correcting bits, which guarantees it is possible to set the error-correcting bits so that the index-XOR of the whole message is 0.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the receiver receives a string with index-XOR 0, they can conclude there were no corruptions, and otherwise, the index-XOR indicates the index of the corrupted bit.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] All bit positions that are powers of two (have a single 1 bit in the binary form of their position) are parity bits: 1, 2, 4, 8, etc.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] All other bit positions, with two or more 1 bits in the binary form of their position, are data bits.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Each data bit is included in a unique set of 2 or more parity bits, as determined by the binary form of its bit position.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Parity bit 2 covers all bit positions which have the **second** least significant bit set: bits 2–3, 6–7, 10–11, etc.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Parity bit 4 covers all bit positions which have the **third** least significant bit set: bits 4–7, 12–15, 20–23, etc.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Parity bit 8 covers all bit positions which have the **fourth** least significant bit set: bits 8–15, 24–31, 40–47, etc.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In general each parity bit covers all bits where the bitwise AND of the parity position and the bit position is non-zero.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If a byte of data to be encoded is 10011010, then the data word (using _ to represent the parity bits) would be __1_001_1010, and the code word is 011100101010.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The choice of the parity, even or odd, is irrelevant but the same choice must be used for both encoding and decoding.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Shown are only 20 encoded bits (5 parity, 15 data) but the pattern continues indefinitely.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The key thing about Hamming codes that can be seen from visual inspection is that any given bit is included in a unique set of parity bits.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] To check for errors, check all of the parity bits.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The pattern of errors, called the error syndrome, identifies the bit in error.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If all parity bits are correct, there is no error.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Otherwise, the sum of the positions of the erroneous parity bits identifies the erroneous bit.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] For example, if the parity bits in positions 1, 2 and 8 indicate an error, then bit 1+2+8=11 is in error.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If only one parity bit indicates an error, the parity bit itself is in error.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] With m parity bits, bits from 1 up to $2^{m}-1$ can be covered.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] After discounting the parity bits, $2^{m}-m-1$ bits remain for use as data.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Hamming codes have a minimum distance of 3, which means that the decoder can detect and correct a single error, but it cannot distinguish a double bit error of some codeword from a single bit error of a different codeword.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Thus, some double-bit errors will be incorrectly decoded as if they were single bit errors and therefore go undetected, unless no correction is attempted.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] To remedy this shortcoming, Hamming codes can be extended by an extra parity bit.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] This way, it is possible to increase the minimum distance of the Hamming code to 4, which allows the decoder to distinguish between single bit errors and two-bit errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Thus the decoder can detect and correct a single error and at the same time detect (but not correct) a double error.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the decoder does not attempt to correct errors, it can reliably detect triple bit errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the decoder does correct errors, some triple errors will be mistaken for single errors and "corrected" to the wrong value.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Error correction is therefore a trade-off between certainty (the ability to reliably detect triple bit errors) and resiliency (the ability to keep functioning in the face of single bit errors).
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] This extended Hamming code was popular in computer memory systems, starting with IBM 7030 Stretch in 1961, where it is known as *SECDED* (or SEC-DED, abbreviated from *single error correction, double error detection*).
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Common forms for memory systems include (39,32) and (72,64).
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The (72,64) Hamming code is still popular in some hardware designs, including Xilinx FPGA families.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] In 1950, Hamming introduced the [7,4] Hamming code.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] It encodes four data bits into seven bits by adding three parity bits.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] As explained earlier, it can either detect and correct single-bit errors or it can detect (but not correct) both single and double-bit errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] With the addition of an overall parity bit, it becomes the [8,4] extended Hamming code and can both detect and correct single-bit errors and detect (but not correct) double-bit errors.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] and $\mathbf {H} :={\begin{pmatrix}{\begin{array}{c|c}A&I_{n-k}\\\end{array}}\end{pmatrix}}$ is called a parity-check matrix.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] This is the construction of **G** and **H** in standard (or systematic) form.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The parity-check matrix **H** of a Hamming code is constructed by listing all columns of length *m* that are pair-wise independent.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Thus **H** is a matrix whose left side is all of the nonzero *n*-tuples where order of the *n*-tuples in the columns of matrix does not matter.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The right hand side is just the (*n* − *k*)-identity matrix.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] So **G** can be obtained from **H** by taking the transpose of the left hand side of **H** with the identity *k*-identity matrix on the left hand side of **G**.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] From the above matrix we have 2k = 24 = 16 codewords.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The codeword ${\vec {x}}$ for any of the 16 possible data vectors ${\vec {a}}$ is given by the standard matrix product ${\vec {x}}={\vec {a}}G$ where the summing operation is done modulo-2.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The [7,4] Hamming code can easily be extended to an [8,4] code by adding an extra parity bit on top of the (7,4) encoded word (see Hamming(7,4)).
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] For example, the first row in this matrix is the sum of the second and third rows of H in non-systematic form.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The non-systematic form of G can be row reduced (using elementary row operations) to match this matrix.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The addition of the fourth row effectively computes the sum of all the codeword bits (data and parity) as the fourth parity bit.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] For example, 1011 is encoded (using the non-systematic form of G at the start of this section) into 01100110 where blue digits are data; red digits are parity bits from the [7,4] Hamming code; and the green digit is the parity bit added by the [8,4] code.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] The green digit makes the parity of the [7,4] codewords even.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Finally, it can be shown that the minimum distance has increased from 3, in the [7,4] code, to 4 in the [8,4] code.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Therefore, the code can be defined as [8,4] Hamming code.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] To decode the [8,4] Hamming code, first check the parity bit.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the parity bit indicates an error, single error correction (the [7,4] Hamming code) will indicate the error location, with "no error" indicating the parity bit.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the parity bit is correct, then single error correction will indicate the (bitwise) exclusive-or of two error locations.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] If the locations are equal ("no error") then a double bit error either has not occurred, or has cancelled itself out.
[src:information-theory/hamming-code] Otherwise, a double bit error has occurred.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theory was initially formed in the context of telecommunication but soon found a wide range of other applications.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] It is now at the intersection of mathematics, statistics and computer science, and has applications in diverse fields ranging from electrical engineering and physics to neurobiology.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] As a simple example of the concept, if one flips a fair coin and does not yet know the outcome (heads or tails), then they lack a certain amount of information.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] After looking at the coin, they gain information about the outcome.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] For a fair coin, the probability of either heads or tails is 1/2 and the amount of information is expressed as $-\log _{2}(1/2)$ = 1 bit of information.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A key concept in information theory is entropy.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In Shannon's formulation entropy is equal to the lack of information about an event.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In the above coin flip example, the entropy in the case where you don't know the outcome is 1 bit.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] When you know the outcome after the coin has landed, the entropy is zero because you have gained one bit.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theory has been used in a wide range of applications, such as source coding/data compression (e.g. for ZIP files), and channel coding/error detection and correction (e.g. for DSL).
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Its impact has been crucial to the success of the Voyager missions to deep space, the invention of the compact disc, the feasibility of mobile phones and the development of the Internet and artificial intelligence.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theory, as conceived by Claude Shannon, studies the processing and utilization of information within a probabilistic context.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Abstractly, in this approach information can be thought of as the resolution of uncertainty.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Shannon's main result, the noisy-channel coding theorem, showed that, in the limit of many channel uses, the rate of information that is asymptotically achievable is equal to the channel capacity, a quantity dependent merely on the statistics of the channel over which the messages are sent.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Coding theory is concerned with finding explicit methods, called *codes*, for increasing the efficiency and reducing the error rate of data communication over noisy channels to near the channel capacity.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] These codes can be roughly subdivided into data compression (source coding) and error-correction (channel coding) techniques.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In the latter case, it took many years to find the methods Shannon's work proved were possible.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A third class of information theory codes are cryptographic algorithms (both codes and ciphers).
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Concepts, methods and results from coding theory and information theory are widely used in cryptography and cryptanalysis, such as the unit ban.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The landmark event *establishing* the discipline of information theory and bringing it to immediate worldwide attention was the publication of Claude Shannon's classic paper "A Mathematical Theory of Communication" in the *Bell System Technical Journal* in July and October 1948.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Historian James Gleick rated the paper as the most important development of 1948, noting that the paper was "even more profound and more fundamental" than the transistor.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] He came to be known as the "father of information theory".
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Shannon outlined some of his initial ideas of information theory as early as 1939 in a letter to Vannevar Bush.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Prior to this paper, limited information-theoretic ideas had been developed at Bell Labs, all implicitly assuming events of equal probability.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The unit of information was therefore the decimal digit, which since has sometimes been called the hartley in his honor as a unit or scale or measure of information.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Alan Turing in 1940 used similar ideas as part of the statistical analysis of the breaking of the German second world war Enigma ciphers.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Much of the mathematics behind information theory with events of different probabilities were developed for the field of thermodynamics by Ludwig Boltzmann and J.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Connections between information-theoretic entropy and thermodynamic entropy, including the important contributions by Rolf Landauer in the 1960s, are explored in *Entropy in thermodynamics and information theory*.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The fundamental problem of communication is that of reproducing at one point, either exactly or approximately, a message selected at another point.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theory is based on probability theory and statistics, where quantified information is usually described in terms of bits.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theory often concerns itself with measures of information of the distributions associated with random variables.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] One of the most important measures is called entropy, which forms the building block of many other measures.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Entropy allows quantification of measure of information in a single random variable.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Another useful concept is mutual information defined on two random variables, which quantifies the dependence between those variables, which is done by comparing the conditional and unconditional distributions.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The former quantity is a property of the probability distribution of a random variable and gives a limit on the rate at which data generated by independent samples with the given distribution can be reliably compressed.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The latter is a property of the joint distribution of two random variables and is the maximum rate of reliable communication across a noisy channel in the limit of long block lengths, when the channel statistics are determined by the joint distribution.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The choice of logarithmic base in the following formulae determines the unit of information entropy that is used.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A common unit of information is the bit or shannon, based on the binary logarithm.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Other units include the nat, which is based on the natural logarithm, and the decimal digit, which is based on the common logarithm.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In what follows, an expression of the form *p* log *p* is considered by convention to be equal to zero whenever *p* = 0.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] This is justified because $\lim _{p\rightarrow 0^{+}}p\log p=0$ for any logarithmic base.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Based on the probability mass function of a source, the Shannon entropy *H*, in units of bits per symbol, is defined as the expected value of the information content of the symbols.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The amount of information conveyed by an individual source symbol $x_{i}$ with probability $p_{i}$ is known as its **self-information** or **surprisal**, $I(p_{i})$ .
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A less probable symbol has a larger surprisal, meaning its occurrence provides more information.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Intuitively, the entropy $H(X)$ of a discrete random variable *X* is a measure of the amount of *uncertainty* associated with the value of X when only its distribution is known.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A high entropy indicates the outcomes are more evenly distributed, making the result harder to predict.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] For example, if one transmits 1000 bits (0s and 1s), and the value of each of these bits is known to the receiver (has a specific value with certainty) ahead of transmission, no information is transmitted.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] If, however, each bit is independently and equally likely to be 0 or 1, 1000 shannons of information (more often called bits) have been transmitted.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A key property of entropy is that it is maximized when all the messages in the message space are equiprobable.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] This maximum value represents the most unpredictable state.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] For a source that emits a sequence of N symbols that are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.), the total entropy of the message is $N\cdot H$ bits.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] If the source data symbols are identically distributed but not independent, the entropy of a message of length N will be less than $N\cdot H$ .
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The special case of information entropy for a random variable with two outcomes (a Bernoulli trial) is the **binary entropy function**.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] This is typically calculated using a base-2 logarithm, and its unit is the shannon.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] If one outcome has probability p, the other has probability *1* − *p*.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] This function is depicted in the plot shown above, reaching its maximum of 1 bit when *p* = 0.5, corresponding to the highest uncertainty.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The *joint entropy* of two discrete random variables *X* and *Y* is merely the entropy of their pairing: (*X*, *Y*).
[src:information-theory/information-theory] This implies that if *X* and *Y* are independent, then their joint entropy is the sum of their individual entropies.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] For example, if (*X*, *Y*) represents the position of a chess piece—*X* the row and *Y* the column, then the joint entropy of the row of the piece and the column of the piece will be the entropy of the position of the piece.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Despite similar notation, joint entropy should not be confused with *cross-entropy*.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Thus, joint entropy is just a subcase of entropy where the random variable is a vector giving values in the product space.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Because entropy can be conditioned on a random variable or on that random variable being a certain value, care should be taken not to confuse these two definitions of conditional entropy, the former of which is in more common use.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] where SI (*S*pecific mutual Information) is the pointwise mutual information.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] That is, knowing ${\textstyle Y}$ , we can save an average of *I*(*X*; *Y*) bits in encoding *X* compared to not knowing Y .
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In other words, this is a measure of how much, on the average, the probability distribution on X will change if we are given the value of *${\textstyle Y}$*.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The *Kullback–Leibler divergence* (or *information divergence*, *information gain*, or *relative entropy*) is a way of comparing two distributions: a "true" probability distribution ⁠ $p(X)$ ⁠, and an arbitrary probability distribution ⁠ $q(X)$ ⁠.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] If we compress data in a manner that assumes ⁠ $q(X)$ ⁠ is the distribution underlying some data, when, in reality, ⁠ $p(X)$ ⁠ is the correct distribution, the Kullback–Leibler divergence is the number of average additional bits per datum necessary for compression.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Although it is sometimes used as a 'distance metric', KL divergence is not a true metric since it is not symmetric and does not satisfy the triangle inequality (making it a semi-quasimetric).
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Another interpretation of the KL divergence is the "unnecessary surprise" introduced by a prior from the truth: suppose a number *X* is about to be drawn randomly from a discrete set with probability distribution ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] If Alice knows the true distribution ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠, while Bob believes (has a prior) that the distribution is ⁠ $q(x)$ ⁠, then Bob will be more surprised than Alice, on average, upon seeing the value of X .
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The KL divergence is the (objective) expected value of Bob's (subjective) surprisal minus Alice's surprisal, measured in bits if the *log* is in base 2.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In this way, the extent to which Bob's prior is "wrong" can be quantified in terms of how "unnecessarily surprised" it is expected to make him.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The Kullback Leibler information provides a link between information theory and hypothesis testing, as it is the optimal error exponent in asymmetric hypothesis testing.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In contrast to *mutual* information, *directed* information is not symmetric.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The $I(X^{n}\to Y^{n})$ measures the information bits that are transmitted causally from $X^{n}$ to $Y^{n}$ .
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Other important information theoretic quantities include the Rényi entropy and the Tsallis entropy (generalizations of the concept of entropy), differential entropy (a generalization of quantities of information to continuous distributions), and the conditional mutual information.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Also, pragmatic information has been proposed as a measure of how much information has been used in making a decision.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Coding theory is one of the most important and direct applications of information theory.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] It can be subdivided into source coding theory and channel coding theory.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Using a statistical description for data, information theory quantifies the number of bits needed to describe the data, which is the information entropy of the source.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] This division of coding theory into compression and transmission is justified by the information transmission theorems, or source–channel separation theorems that justify the use of bits as the universal currency for information in many contexts.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] However, these theorems only hold in the situation where one transmitting user wishes to communicate to one receiving user.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In scenarios with more than one transmitter (the multiple-access channel), more than one receiver (the broadcast channel) or intermediary "helpers" (the relay channel), or more general networks, compression followed by transmission may no longer be optimal.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] For general sources and channels that are not necessarily stationary or ergodic, information-spectrum methods characterize coding limits using asymptotic distributions of information density rather than only single-letter entropies or mutual information.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A related problem, channel resolvability, asks what rate is required for channel inputs to approximate a target output distribution; Han and Sergio Verdú connected this approximation problem to coding theorems for general channels.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Any process that generates successive messages can be considered a *source* of information.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A memoryless source is one in which each message is an independent identically distributed random variable, whereas the properties of ergodicity and stationarity impose less restrictive constraints.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] These terms are well studied in their own right outside information theory.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information *rate* is the average entropy per symbol.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] that is, the conditional entropy of a symbol given all the previous symbols generated.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] that is, the limit of the joint entropy per symbol.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] For stationary sources, these two expressions give the same result.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] It is common in information theory to speak of the "rate" or "entropy" of a language.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] This is appropriate, for example, when the source of information is English prose.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The rate of a source of information is related to its redundancy and how well it can be compressed, the subject of *source coding*.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Communications over a channel is the primary motivation of information theory.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] However, channels often fail to produce exact reconstruction of a signal; noise, periods of silence, and other forms of signal corruption often degrade quality.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Consider the communications process over a discrete channel.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Here X represents the space of messages transmitted, and ${\textstyle Y}$ the space of messages received during a unit time over our channel.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Let *p*(*y*|*x*) be the conditional probability distribution function of *${\textstyle Y}$* given X .
[src:information-theory/information-theory] We will consider *p*(*y*|*x*) to be an inherent fixed property of our communications channel (representing the nature of the *noise* of our channel).
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Then the joint distribution of *X* and *${\textstyle Y}$* is completely determined by our channel and by our choice of *f*(*x*), the marginal distribution of messages we choose to send over the channel.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Under these constraints, we would like to maximize the rate of information, or the *signal*, we can communicate over the channel.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] This capacity has the following property related to communicating at information rate *R* (where *R* is usually bits per symbol).
[src:information-theory/information-theory] For any information rate *R* < *C* and coding error *ε* > 0, for large enough *N*, there exists a code of length *N* and rate ≥ R and a decoding algorithm, such that the maximal probability of block error is ≤ *ε*; that is, it is always possible to transmit with arbitrarily small block error.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In addition, for any rate *R* > *C*, it is impossible to transmit with arbitrarily small block error.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In such a case the capacity is given by the mutual information rate when there is no feedback available and the Directed information rate in the case that either there is feedback or not (if there is no feedback the directed information equals the mutual information).
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theoretic concepts apply to cryptography and cryptanalysis.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Turing's information unit, the ban, was used in the Ultra project, breaking the German Enigma machine code and hastening the end of World War II in Europe.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Shannon himself defined an important concept now called the unicity distance.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Based on the redundancy of the plaintext, it attempts to give a minimum amount of ciphertext necessary to ensure unique decipherability.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theory leads us to believe it is much more difficult to keep secrets than it might first appear.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A brute force attack can break systems based on asymmetric key algorithms or on most commonly used methods of symmetric key algorithms (sometimes called secret key algorithms), such as block ciphers.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The security of all such methods comes from the assumption that no known attack can break them in a practical amount of time.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theoretic security refers to methods such as the one-time pad that are not vulnerable to such brute force attacks.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In such cases, the positive conditional mutual information between the plaintext and ciphertext (conditioned on the key) can ensure proper transmission, while the unconditional mutual information between the plaintext and ciphertext remains zero, resulting in absolutely secure communications.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] In other words, an eavesdropper would not be able to improve his or her guess of the plaintext by gaining knowledge of the ciphertext but not of the key.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] However, as in any other cryptographic system, care must be used to correctly apply even information-theoretically secure methods; the Venona project was able to crack the one-time pads of the Soviet Union due to their improper reuse of key material.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Pseudorandom number generators are widely available in computer language libraries and application programs.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] They are, almost universally, unsuited to cryptographic use as they do not evade the deterministic nature of modern computer equipment and software.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] A class of improved random number generators is termed cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators, but even they require random seeds external to the software to work as intended.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] These can be obtained via extractors, if done carefully.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] The measure of sufficient randomness in extractors is min-entropy, a value related to Shannon entropy through Rényi entropy; Rényi entropy is also used in evaluating randomness in cryptographic systems.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Although related, the distinctions among these measures mean that a random variable with high Shannon entropy is not necessarily satisfactory for use in an extractor and so for cryptography uses.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] One early commercial application of information theory was in the field of seismic oil exploration.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Work in this field made it possible to strip off and separate the unwanted noise from the desired seismic signal.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theory and digital signal processing offer a major improvement of resolution and image clarity over previous analog methods.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Semioticians Doede Nauta and Winfried Nöth both considered Charles Sanders Peirce as having created a theory of information in his works on semiotics.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Quantitative information theoretic methods have been applied in cognitive science to analyze the integrated process organization of neural information in the context of the binding problem in cognitive neuroscience.
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Friston's free energy principle (FEP), an information-theoretical measure which states that every adaptive change in a self-organized system leads to a minimization of free energy, and the Bayesian brain hypothesis).
[src:information-theory/information-theory] Information theory also has applications in the search for extraterrestrial intelligence, black holes, bioinformatics, and gambling.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] In algorithmic information theory (a subfield of computer science and mathematics), the **Kolmogorov complexity** of an object, such as a piece of text, is the length of a shortest computer program (in a predetermined programming language) that produces the object as output.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It is a measure of the computational resources needed to specify the object, and is also known as **algorithmic complexity**, **Solomonoff–Kolmogorov–Chaitin complexity**, **program-size complexity**, **descriptive complexity**, or **algorithmic entropy**.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It is named after Andrey Kolmogorov, who first published on the subject in 1963 and is a generalization of classical information theory.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The notion of Kolmogorov complexity can be used to state and prove impossibility results akin to Cantor's diagonal argument, Gödel's incompleteness theorem, and Turing's halting problem.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] In particular, no program *P* computing a lower bound for each text's Kolmogorov complexity can return a value essentially larger than *P*'s own length (see section § Chaitin's incompleteness theorem); hence no single program can compute the exact Kolmogorov complexity for infinitely many texts.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The first string has a short English-language description, namely "write ab 16 times", which consists of **17** characters.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The second one has no obvious simple description (using the same character set) other than writing down the string itself, i.e., "write 4c1j5b2p0cv4w1x8rx2y39umgw5q85s7" which has **38** characters.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Hence the operation of writing the first string can be said to have "less complexity" than writing the second.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] More formally, the complexity of a string is the length of the shortest possible description of the string in some fixed universal description language (the sensitivity of complexity relative to the choice of description language is discussed below).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It can be shown that the Kolmogorov complexity of any string cannot be more than a few bytes larger than the length of the string itself.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Strings like the *abab* example above, whose Kolmogorov complexity is small relative to the string's size, are not considered to be complex.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The Kolmogorov complexity can be defined for any mathematical object, but for simplicity the scope of this article is restricted to strings.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] We must first specify a description language for strings.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Such a description language can be based on any computer programming language, such as Lisp, Pascal, or Java.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] If **P** is a program which outputs a string *x*, then **P** is a description of *x*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The length of the description is just the length of **P** as a character string, multiplied by the number of bits in a character (e.g., 7 for ASCII).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] We could, alternatively, choose an encoding for Turing machines, where an *encoding* is a function which associates to each Turing Machine **M** a bitstring <**M**>.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] If **M** is a Turing Machine which, on input *w*, outputs string *x*, then the concatenated string <**M**> *w* is a description of *x*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] For theoretical analysis, this approach is more suited for constructing detailed formal proofs and is generally preferred in the research literature.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] In this article, an informal approach is discussed.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Any string *s* has at least one description.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] If a description *d*(*s*) of a string *s* is of minimal length (i.e., using the fewest bits), it is called a **minimal description** of *s*, and the length of *d*(*s*) (i.e. the number of bits in the minimal description) is the **Kolmogorov complexity** of *s*, written *K*(*s*).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The length of the shortest description will depend on the choice of description language; but the effect of changing languages is bounded (a result called the *invariance theorem*, see below).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] There are two definitions of Kolmogorov complexity: *plain* and *prefix-free*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The plain complexity is the minimal description length of any program, and denoted $C(x)$ while the prefix-free complexity is the minimal description length of any program encoded in a prefix-free code, and denoted $K(x)$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The plain complexity is more intuitive, but the prefix-free complexity is easier to study.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] By default, all equations hold only up to an additive constant.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Let $U:2^{*}\to 2^{*}$ be a computable function mapping finite binary strings to binary strings.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It is a universal function if, and only if, for any computable $f:2^{*}\to 2^{*}$ , we can encode the function in a "program" $s_{f}$ , such that $\forall x\in 2^{*},U(s_{f}x)=f(x)$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] We can think of U as a program interpreter, which takes in an initial segment describing the program, followed by data that the program should process.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] One problem with plain complexity is that $C(xy)\not <C(x)+C(y)$ , because intuitively speaking, there is no general way to tell where to divide an output string just by looking at the concatenated string.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] We can divide it by specifying the length of x or y , but that would take $O(\min(\ln x,\ln y))$ extra symbols.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Indeed, for any $c>0$ there exists $x,y$ such that $C(xy)\geq C(x)+C(y)+c$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Typically, inequalities with plain complexity have a term like $O(\min(\ln x,\ln y))$ on one side, whereas the same inequalities with prefix-free complexity have only $O(1)$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The main problem with plain complexity is that there is something extra sneaked into a program.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] A program not only represents for something with its code, but also represents its own length.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] In particular, a program x may represent a binary number up to $\log _{2}|x|$ , simply by its own length.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Stated in another way, it is as if we are using a termination symbol to denote where a word ends, and so we are not using 2 symbols, but 3.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] To fix this defect, we introduce the prefix-free Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] A **prefix-free universal Turing machine** is a universal partial computable function $U:2^{*}\rightarrow 2^{*}$ whose domain is a prefix-free set of binary strings.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Equivalently, no valid program for U is a prefix of any other, the domain satisfies the prefix property.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] For instance, if every valid program for a universal Turing machine U ended with a termination string that could not appear elsewhere in the program, U would be prefix-free.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The prefix-free Kolmogorov complexity of a string x is defined by $K(x):=\min\{|c|:U(c)=x\}$ the length of the shortest self-delimiting program that causes U to output x .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Different choices of prefix-free universal machines change $K(x)$ by at most an additive constant.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] There are some description languages which are optimal, in the following sense: given any description of an object in a description language, said description may be used in the optimal description language with a constant overhead.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The constant depends only on the languages involved, not on the description of the object, nor the object being described.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Here is an example of an optimal description language.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] In more technical terms, the first part of a description is a computer program (specifically: a compiler for the object's language, written in the description language), with the second part being the input to that computer program which produces the object as output.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The length of *P* is a constant that doesn't depend on *D*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] So, there is at most a constant overhead, regardless of the object described.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Therefore, the optimal language is universal up to this additive constant.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Thus, if **P** is a program in *L*2 which is a minimal description of *s*, then `interpret_language`(**P**) returns the string *s*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The length of **P** which by definition is *K*2(*s*).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Algorithmic information theory is the area of computer science that studies Kolmogorov complexity and other complexity measures on strings (or other data structures).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The concept and theory of Kolmogorov Complexity is based on a crucial theorem first discovered by Ray Solomonoff, who published it in 1960, describing it in "A Preliminary Report on a General Theory of Inductive Inference" as part of his invention of algorithmic probability.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] He gave a more complete description in his 1964 publications, "A Formal Theory of Inductive Inference," Part 1 and Part 2 in *Information and Control*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Andrey Kolmogorov later independently published this theorem in *Problems Inform.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Gregory Chaitin also presents this theorem in the *Journal of the ACM* – Chaitin's paper was submitted October 1966 and revised in December 1968, and cites both Solomonoff's and Kolmogorov's papers.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The theorem says that, among algorithms that decode strings from their descriptions (codes), there exists an optimal one.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] This algorithm, for all strings, allows codes as short as allowed by any other algorithm up to an additive constant that depends on the algorithms, but not on the strings themselves.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Solomonoff used this algorithm and the code lengths it allows to define a "universal probability" of a string on which inductive inference of the subsequent digits of the string can be based.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Kolmogorov used this theorem to define several functions of strings, including complexity, randomness, and information.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] When Kolmogorov became aware of Solomonoff's work, he acknowledged Solomonoff's priority.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] For several years, Solomonoff's work was better known in the Soviet Union than in the West.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The broader area encompassing descriptional complexity and probability is often called Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] There are several other variants of Kolmogorov complexity or algorithmic information.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The most widely used one is based on self-delimiting programs, and is mainly due to Leonid Levin (1974).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] An axiomatic approach to Kolmogorov complexity based on Blum axioms (Blum 1967) was introduced by Mark Burgin in the paper presented for publication by Andrey Kolmogorov.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] We write $K(x,y)$ to be $K((x,y))$ , where $(x,y)$ means some fixed way to code for a tuple of strings x and y.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Note that there is no way to compare $K(xy)$ and $K(x|y)$ or $K(x)$ or $K(y|x)$ or $K(y)$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] There are strings such that the whole string $xy$ is easy to describe, but its substrings are very hard to describe.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] This program iterates through all possible programs (by iterating through all possible strings and only considering those which are valid programs), starting with the shortest.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Each program is executed to find the result produced by that program, comparing it to the input *s*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] If the result matches then the length of the program is returned.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] However this will not work because some of the programs *p* tested will not terminate, e.g. if they contain infinite loops.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] There is no way to avoid all of these programs by testing them in some way before executing them due to the non-computability of the halting problem.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] What is more, no program at all can compute the function *K*, be it ever so sophisticated.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The following **proof** by contradiction uses a simple Pascal-like language to denote programs; for sake of proof simplicity assume its description (i.e. an interpreter) to have a length of 1400000 bits.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] which takes as input a string *s* and returns *K*(*s*).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] All programs are of finite length so, for sake of proof simplicity, assume it to be 7000000000 bits.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Using `kolmogorov_complexity` as a subroutine, the program tries every string, starting with the shortest, until it returns a string with Kolmogorov complexity at least 8000000000 bits, i.e. a string that cannot be produced by any program shorter than 8000000000 bits.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] However, the overall length of the above program that produced *s* is only 7001401288 bits, which is a contradiction.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] (If the code of `KolmogorovComplexity` is shorter, the contradiction remains.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The above proof uses a contradiction similar to that of the Berry paradox: "1The 2smallest 3positive 4integer 5that 6cannot 7be 8defined 9in 10fewer 11than 12twenty 13English 14words".
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It is also possible to show the non-computability of *K* by reduction from the non-computability of the halting problem *H*, since *K* and *H* are Turing-equivalent.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] There is a corollary, humorously called the "full employment theorem" in the programming language community, stating that there is no perfect size-optimizing compiler.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It states that the shortest program that reproduces *X* and *Y* is no more than a logarithmic term larger than a program to reproduce *X* and a program to reproduce *Y* given *X*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Using this statement, one can define an analogue of mutual information for Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] A string *s* is compressible by a number *c* if it has a description whose length does not exceed |*s*| − *c* bits.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] This is equivalent to saying that *K*(*s*) ≤ |*s*| − *c*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Otherwise, *s* is incompressible by *c*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] For the same reason, most strings are complex in the sense that they cannot be significantly compressed – their *K*(*s*) is not much smaller than |*s*|, the length of *s* in bits.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] To make this precise, fix a value of *n*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] There are 2*n* bitstrings of length *n*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The uniform probability distribution on the space of these bitstrings assigns exactly equal weight 2−*n* to each string of length *n*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] bitstrings of length *n* that are incompressible by *c*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] To determine the probability, divide by 2*n*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] By the above theorem (§ Compression), most strings are complex in the sense that they cannot be described in any significantly "compressed" way.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] However, it turns out that the fact that a specific string is complex cannot be formally proven, if the complexity of the string is above a certain threshold.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The precise formalization is as follows.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] First, fix a particular axiomatic system **S** for the natural numbers.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The axiomatic system has to be powerful enough so that, to certain assertions **A** about complexity of strings, one can associate a formula **F****A** in **S**.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] If **F****A** is provable from the axioms of **S**, then the corresponding assertion **A** must be true.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] This "formalization" can be achieved based on a Gödel numbering.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] which takes as input *n* and outputs some proof.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Some of these are proofs for formulas we do not care about here, since every possible proof in the language of **S** is produced for some *n*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Some of these are complexity formulas of the form *K*(*s*) ≥ *n* where *s* and *n* are constants in the language of **S**.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] which determines whether the *n*th proof actually proves a complexity formula *K*(*s*) ≥ *L*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Given an n , this procedure tries every proof until it finds a string and a proof in the formal system **S** of the formula $K(s)\geq L$ for some $L\geq n$ ; if no such proof exists, it loops forever.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] where the constant $n_{0}$ will be determined later on.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The overall program length can be expressed as $U+log_{2}(n_{0})$ , where U is some constant and $log_{2}(n_{0})$ represents the length of the integer value $n_{0}$ , under the reasonable assumption that it is encoded in binary digits.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] We will choose $n_{0}$ to be greater than the program length, that is, such that $n_{0}>U+log_{2}(n_{0})$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] This is clearly true for $n_{0}$ sufficiently large, because the left hand side grows linearly in $n_{0}$ whilst the right hand side grows logarithmically in $n_{0}$ up to the fixed constant U .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] As a consequence, the above program, with the chosen value of $n_{0}$ , must loop forever.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Similar ideas are used to prove the properties of Chaitin's constant.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The minimum message length principle of statistical and inductive inference and machine learning was developed by C.S.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] MML is Bayesian (i.e. it incorporates prior beliefs) and information-theoretic.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Dowe (1999) showed a formal connection between MML and algorithmic information theory (or Kolmogorov complexity).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] This definition can be extended to define a notion of randomness for *infinite* sequences from a finite alphabet.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] These algorithmically random sequences can be defined in three equivalent ways.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] One way uses an effective analogue of measure theory; another uses effective martingales.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The third way defines an infinite sequence to be random if the prefix-free Kolmogorov complexity of its initial segments grows quickly enough — there must be a constant *c* such that the complexity of an initial segment of length *n* is always at least *n*−*c*.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] For dynamical systems, entropy rate and algorithmic complexity of the trajectories are related by a theorem of Brudno, that the equality $K(x;T)=h(T)$ holds for almost all x .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It can be shown that for the output of Markov information sources, Kolmogorov complexity is related to the entropy of the information source.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] More precisely, the Kolmogorov complexity of the output of a Markov information source, normalized by the length of the output, converges almost surely (as the length of the output goes to infinity) to the entropy of the source.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The Kolmogorov complexity function is equivalent to deciding the halting problem.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] If we have a halting oracle, then the Kolmogorov complexity of a string can be computed by simply trying every halting program, in lexicographic order, until one of them outputs the string.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The other direction is much more involved.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It shows that given a Kolmogorov complexity function, we can construct a function p , such that $p(n)\geq BB(n)$ for all large n , where $BB$ is the Busy Beaver shift function (also denoted as $S(n)$ ).
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] By modifying the function at lower values of n we get an upper bound on $BB$ , which solves the halting problem.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Consider this program ${\textstyle p_{K}}$ , which takes input as ${\textstyle n}$ , and uses ${\textstyle K}$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] We prove by contradiction that ${\textstyle p_{K}(n)\geq BB(n)}$ for all large ${\textstyle n}$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Let ${\textstyle p_{n}}$ be a Busy Beaver of length n .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Let the string output by the program be ${\textstyle x}$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The program has length ${\textstyle \leq n+2\log _{2}n+O(1)}$ , where n comes from the length of the Busy Beaver ${\textstyle p_{n}}$ , $2\log _{2}n$ comes from using the (prefix-free) Elias delta code for the number n , and $O(1)$ comes from the rest of the program.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Further, since there are only so many possible programs with length ${\textstyle \leq 2n}$ , we have ${\textstyle l(x)\leq 2n+1}$ by pigeonhole principle.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] By assumption, ${\textstyle p_{K}(n)<BB(n)}$ , so every string of length ${\textstyle \leq 2n+1}$ has a minimal program with runtime ${\textstyle <BB(n)}$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Thus, the string ${\textstyle x}$ has a minimal program with runtime ${\textstyle <BB(n)}$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Further, that program has length ${\textstyle K(x)\leq 2n}$ .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] This contradicts how ${\textstyle x}$ was constructed.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Fix a universal Turing machine U , the same one used to define the (prefix-free) Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Define the (prefix-free) universal probability of a string x to be $P(x)=\sum _{U(p)=x}2^{-l(p)}$ In other words, it is the probability that, given a uniformly random binary stream as input, the universal Turing machine would halt after reading a certain prefix of the stream, and output x .
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Note. $U(p)=x$ does not mean that the input stream is $p000\cdots$ , but that the universal Turing machine would halt at some point after reading the initial segment p , without reading any further input, and that, when it halts, it has written x to the output tape.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Kolmogorov complexity has been used in the context of biology to argue that the symmetries and modular arrangements observed in multiple species emerge from the tendency of evolution to prefer minimal Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Considering the genome as a program that must solve a task or implement a series of functions, shorter programs would be preferred on the basis that they are easier to find by the mechanisms of evolution.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] An example of this approach is the eight-fold symmetry of the compass circuit that is found across insect species, which correspond to the circuit that is both functional and requires the minimum Kolmogorov complexity to be generated from self-replicating units.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] The conditional Kolmogorov complexity of two strings $K(x|y)$ is, roughly speaking, defined as the Kolmogorov complexity of *x* given *y* as an auxiliary input to the procedure.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] There is also a length-conditional complexity $K(x|L(x))$ , which is the complexity of *x* given the length of *x* as known/input.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] Time-bounded Kolmogorov complexity is a modified version of Kolmogorov complexity where the space of programs to be searched for a solution is confined to only programs that can run within some pre-defined number of steps.
[src:information-theory/kolmogorov-complexity] It is hypothesised that the possibility of the existence of an efficient algorithm for determining approximate time-bounded Kolmogorov complexity is related to the question of whether true one-way functions exist.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In information theory and coding theory, **Reed–Solomon codes** are a group of error-correcting codes that were introduced by Irving S.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] They have many applications, including consumer technologies such as MiniDiscs, CDs, DVDs, Blu-ray discs, QR codes, Data Matrix, data transmission technologies such as DSL and WiMAX, broadcast systems such as satellite communications, DVB and ATSC, and storage systems such as RAID 6.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon codes operate on a block of data treated as a set of finite-field elements called symbols.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon codes RS(*n*, *k*) are able to detect and correct multiple symbol errors.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] By adding *t* = *n* − *k* check symbols to the data, a Reed–Solomon code can detect (but not correct) any combination of up to t erroneous symbols, *or* locate and correct up to ⌊*t*/2⌋ erroneous symbols at unknown locations.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] As an erasure code, it can correct up to t erasures at locations that are known and provided to the algorithm, or it can detect and correct combinations of errors and erasures.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon codes are also suitable as multiple-burst bit-error correcting codes, since a sequence of *b* + 1 consecutive bit errors can affect at most two symbols of size b.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The choice of t is up to the designer of the code and may be selected within wide limits.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] There are two different Reed-Solomon encoding schemes, called original view and BCH view in this article.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The history section explains the origins of this.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon codes were developed in 1960 by Irving S.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed and Gustave Solomon, who were then staff members of MIT Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Their seminal article was titled "Polynomial Codes over Certain Finite Fields".
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The original encoding scheme described in the Reed and Solomon article used a variable polynomial based on the message to be encoded where only a fixed set of values (evaluation points) to be encoded are known to encoder and decoder.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The original theoretical decoder generated potential polynomials based on subsets of *k* (unencoded message length) out of *n* (encoded message length) values of a received message, choosing the most popular polynomial as the correct one, which was impractical for all but the simplest of cases.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This was initially resolved by changing the original scheme to a BCH-code compatible scheme based on a fixed polynomial known to both encoder and decoder, but later, practical decoders based on the original scheme were developed, although initially slower than the BCH schemes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The result of this is that there are two main types of Reed–Solomon codes: ones that use the original encoding scheme and ones that use the BCH encoding scheme.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Also in 1960, a practical fixed polynomial decoder for BCH codes developed by Daniel Gorenstein and Neal Zierler was described in an MIT Lincoln Laboratory report by Zierler in January 1960 and later in an article in June 1961.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Gorenstein–Zierler decoder and the related work on BCH codes are described in a book "Error-Correcting Codes" by W.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 1969, an improved BCH scheme decoder was developed by Elwyn Berlekamp and James Massey and has since been known as the Berlekamp–Massey decoding algorithm.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 1975, another improved BCH scheme decoder was developed by Yasuo Sugiyama, based on the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 1977, Reed–Solomon codes were implemented in the Voyager program in the form of concatenated error correction codes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The first commercial application in mass-produced consumer products appeared in 1982 with the compact disc, where two interleaved Reed–Solomon codes are used.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Today, Reed–Solomon codes are widely implemented in digital storage devices and digital communication standards, though they are being slowly replaced by Bose–Chaudhuri–Hocquenghem (BCH) codes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] For example, Reed–Solomon codes are used in the Digital Video Broadcasting (DVB) standard DVB-S, in conjunction with a convolutional inner code, but BCH codes are used with LDPC in its successor, DVB-S2.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 1986, an original scheme decoder known as the Berlekamp–Welch algorithm was developed.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 1996, variations of original scheme decoders called list decoders or soft decoders were developed by Madhu Sudan and others, and work continues on these types of decoders (see Guruswami–Sudan list decoding algorithm).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 2002, another original scheme decoder was developed by Shuhong Gao, based on the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Around 2015 an original scheme syndrome like decoder was developed (author unknown).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon coding is very widely used in mass storage systems to correct the burst errors associated with media defects.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon coding is a key component of the compact disc.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] It was the first use of strong error correction coding in a mass-produced consumer product, and DAT and DVD use similar schemes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In the CD, two layers of Reed–Solomon coding separated by a 28-way convolutional interleaver yields a scheme called Cross-Interleaved Reed–Solomon Coding (CIRC).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The first element of a CIRC decoder is a relatively weak inner (32,28) Reed–Solomon code, shortened from a (255,251) code with 8-bit symbols.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This code can correct up to 2 byte errors per 32-byte block.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] More importantly, it flags as erasures any uncorrectable blocks, i.e., blocks with more than 2 byte errors.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The decoded 28-byte blocks, with erasure indications, are then spread by the deinterleaver to different blocks of the (28,24) outer code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Thanks to the deinterleaving, an erased 28-byte block from the inner code becomes a single erased byte in each of 28 outer code blocks.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The outer code easily corrects this, since it can handle up to 4 such erasures per block.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The result is a CIRC that can completely correct error bursts up to 4000 bits, or about 2.5 mm on the disc surface.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This code is so strong that most CD playback errors are almost certainly caused by tracking errors that cause the laser to jump track, not by uncorrectable error bursts.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] DVDs use a similar scheme, but with much larger blocks, a (208,192) inner code, and a (182,172) outer code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon error correction is also used in parchive files which are commonly posted accompanying multimedia files on USENET.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The distributed online storage service Wuala (discontinued in 2015) also used Reed–Solomon when breaking up files.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Almost all two-dimensional bar codes such as PDF-417, MaxiCode, Datamatrix, QR Code, Aztec Code and Han Xin code use Reed–Solomon error correction to allow correct reading even if a portion of the bar code is damaged.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] When the bar code scanner cannot recognize a bar code symbol, it will treat it as an erasure.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon coding is less common in one-dimensional bar codes, but is used by the PostBar symbology.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Specialized forms of Reed–Solomon codes, specifically Cauchy-RS and Vandermonde-RS, can be used to overcome the unreliable nature of data transmission over erasure channels.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The encoding process assumes a code of RS(*N*, *K*) which results in *N* codewords of length *N* symbols each storing *K* symbols of data, being generated, that are then sent over an erasure channel.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Any combination of *K* codewords received at the other end is enough to reconstruct all of the *N* codewords.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The code rate is generally set to 1/2 unless the channel's erasure likelihood can be adequately modelled and is seen to be less.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In conclusion, *N* is usually 2*K*, meaning that at least half of all the codewords sent must be received in order to reconstruct all of the codewords sent.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon codes are also used in xDSL systems and CCSDS's Space Communications Protocol Specifications as a form of forward error correction.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] One significant application of Reed–Solomon coding was to encode the digital pictures sent back by the Voyager program.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Voyager introduced Reed–Solomon coding concatenated with convolutional codes, a practice that has since become very widespread in deep space and satellite (e.g., direct digital broadcasting) communications.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Viterbi decoders tend to produce errors in short bursts.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Correcting these burst errors is a job best done by short or simplified Reed–Solomon codes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Modern versions of concatenated Reed–Solomon/Viterbi-decoded convolutional coding were and are used on the Mars Pathfinder, Galileo, Mars Exploration Rover and Cassini missions, where they perform within about 1–1.5 dB of the ultimate limit, the Shannon capacity.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Reed–Solomon code is actually a family of codes, where every code is characterised by three parameters: an alphabet size q, a block length n, and a message length k*,* with $k<n\leq q$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The set of alphabet symbols is interpreted as the finite field F of order q , and thus, q must be a prime power.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] There are different encoding procedures for the Reed–Solomon code, and thus, there are different ways to describe the set of all codewords.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In the original view of Reed and Solomon, every codeword of the Reed–Solomon code is a sequence of function values of a polynomial of degree less than k .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In order to obtain a codeword of the Reed–Solomon code, the message symbols (each within the q-sized alphabet) are treated as the coefficients of a polynomial p of degree less than k , over the finite field F with q elements.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In turn, the polynomial p is evaluated at a set of $n\leq q$ distinct points in any order $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ of the field F , and the sequence of values is the corresponding codeword.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Furthermore, there are two polynomials that do agree in $k-1$ points but are not equal, and thus, the distance of the Reed–Solomon code is exactly $d=n-k+1$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Then the relative distance is $\delta =d/n=1-k/n+1/n=1-R+1/n\sim 1-R$ , where $R=k/n$ is the rate.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This trade-off between the relative distance and the rate is asymptotically optimal since, by the Singleton bound, *every* code satisfies $\delta +R\leq 1+1/n$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Being a code that achieves this optimal trade-off, the Reed–Solomon code belongs to the class of maximum distance separable codes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] While the number of different polynomials of degree less than *k* and the number of different messages are both equal to $q^{k}$ , and thus every message can be uniquely mapped to such a polynomial, there are different ways of doing this encoding.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The latter encoding procedure, while being slightly less efficient, has the advantage that it gives rise to a systematic code, that is, the original message is always contained as a subsequence of the codeword.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This function C is a linear mapping, that is, it satisfies $C(m)=mA$ for the following $k\times n$ -matrix A with elements from F .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This matrix is a Vandermonde matrix over F .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In other words, the Reed–Solomon code is a linear code, and in the classical encoding procedure, its generator matrix is A .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] There are alternative encoding procedures that produce a systematic Reed–Solomon code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] One method uses Lagrange interpolation to compute polynomial $p_{m}$ such that $p_{m}(a_{i})=m_{i}{\text{ for all }}i\in \{0,\dots ,k-1\}.$ Then $p_{m}$ is evaluated at the other points $a_{k},\dots ,a_{n-1}$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] To generate the corresponding systematic encoding matrix G, multiply the matrix A by the inverse of A's left square submatrix.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] However, Lagrange interpolation performs the same conversion without the constraint on the set of evaluation points or the requirement of an error free set of message values and is used for systematic encoding, and in one of the steps of the Gao decoder.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Note that BCH Code and most implementations of BCH view are most significant term first.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The sender computes a related polynomial $c(x)$ of degree $n-1$ where $n\leq q-1$ and sends the polynomial $c(x)$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The polynomial $c(x)$ is constructed by multiplying the message polynomial $m(x)$ , which has degree $k-1$ , with the generator polynomial $g(x)$ of degree $n-k$ that is known to both the sender and the receiver. $c(x)=m(x)g(x)$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] $C(m)=mA$ for the following $k\times n$ matrix G with elements from F .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The encoding procedure for the BCH view of Reed–Solomon codes can be modified to yield a systematic encoding procedure, in which each codeword contains the message as a prefix, and simply appends error correcting symbols as a suffix.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Then the coefficients of $m(x)$ are a subsequence of the coefficients of $c(x)$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] To get a code that is overall systematic, we construct the message polynomial $c(x)$ by interpreting the message as the sequence of its coefficients.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Formally, the construction is done by multiplying $c(x)$ by $x^{t}$ to make room for the $t=n-k$ check symbols, dividing that product by $g(x)$ to find the remainder, and then compensating for that remainder by subtracting it.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The remainder has degree at most $t-1$ , whereas the coefficients of $x^{t-1},x^{t-2},\dots ,x^{1},x^{0}$ in the polynomial $c(x)\cdot x^{t}$ are zero.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] To generate the corresponding systematic encoding matrix G, multiply the matrix A by the inverse of A's left square submatrix (or set G's left square submatrix to the identity matrix and encode each row).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] $C(m)=mG$ for the following $k\times n$ matrix G with elements from F .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Such a code is also called a maximum distance separable (MDS) code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The error-correcting ability of a Reed–Solomon code is determined by its minimum distance, or equivalently, by $n-k$ , the measure of redundancy in the block.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] If the locations of the error symbols are not known in advance, then a Reed–Solomon code can correct up to $(n-k)/2$ erroneous symbols, i.e., it can correct half as many errors as there are redundant symbols added to the block.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Sometimes error locations are known in advance (e.g., "side information" in demodulator signal-to-noise ratios)—these are called erasures.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] A Reed–Solomon code (like any MDS code) is able to correct twice as many erasures as errors, and any combination of errors and erasures can be corrected as long as the relation 2*E* + *S* ≤ *n* − *k* is satisfied, where E is the number of errors and S is the number of erasures in the block.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] For practical uses of Reed–Solomon codes, it is common to use a finite field F with $2^{m}$ elements.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In this case, each symbol can be represented as an m -bit value.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The sender sends the data points as encoded blocks, and the number of symbols in the encoded block is $n=2^{m}-1$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Thus a Reed–Solomon code operating on 8-bit symbols has $n=2^{8}-1=255$ symbols per block.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] (This is a very popular value because of the prevalence of byte-oriented computer systems.) The number k , with $k<n$ , of *data* symbols in the block is a design parameter.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] A commonly used code encodes $k=223$ eight-bit data symbols plus 32 eight-bit parity symbols in an $n=255$ -symbol block; this is denoted as a $(n,k)=(255,223)$ code, and is capable of correcting up to 16 symbol errors per block.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Reed–Solomon code properties discussed above make them especially well-suited to applications where errors occur in bursts.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This is because it does not matter to the code how many bits in a symbol are in error — if multiple bits in a symbol are corrupted it only counts as a single error.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Conversely, if a data stream is not characterized by error bursts or drop-outs but by random single bit errors, a Reed–Solomon code is usually a poor choice compared to a binary code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Reed–Solomon code, like the convolutional code, is a transparent code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This means that if the channel symbols have been inverted somewhere along the line, the decoders will still operate.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The result will be the inversion of the original data.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] However, the Reed–Solomon code loses its transparency when the code is shortened (*see 'Remarks' at the end of this section*).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The "missing" bits in a shortened code need to be filled by either zeros or ones, depending on whether the data is complemented or not.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] (To put it another way, if the symbols are inverted, then the zero-fill needs to be inverted to a one-fill.) For this reason it is mandatory that the sense of the data (i.e., true or complemented) be resolved before Reed–Solomon decoding.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Whether the Reed–Solomon code is cyclic or not depends on subtle details of the construction.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In the original view of Reed and Solomon, where the codewords are the values of a polynomial, one can choose the sequence of evaluation points in such a way as to make the code cyclic.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In particular, if $\alpha$ is a primitive root of the field F , then by definition all non-zero elements of F take the form $\alpha ^{i}$ for $i\in \{1,\dots ,q-1\}$ , where $q=|F|$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Each polynomial p over F gives rise to a codeword $(p(\alpha ^{1}),\dots ,p(\alpha ^{q-1}))$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Since the function $a\mapsto p(\alpha a)$ is also a polynomial of the same degree, this function gives rise to a codeword $(p(\alpha ^{2}),\dots ,p(\alpha ^{q}))$ ; since $\alpha ^{q}=\alpha ^{1}$ holds, this codeword is the cyclic left-shift of the original codeword derived from p .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] So choosing a sequence of primitive root powers as the evaluation points makes the original view Reed–Solomon code cyclic.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Reed–Solomon codes in the BCH view are always cyclic because BCH codes are cyclic.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Designers are not required to use the "natural" sizes of Reed–Solomon code blocks.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] A technique known as "shortening" can produce a smaller code of any desired size from a larger code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] For example, the widely used (255,223) code can be converted to a (160,128) code by padding the unused portion of the source block with 95 binary zeroes and not transmitting them.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] At the decoder, the same portion of the block is loaded locally with binary zeroes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The QR code, Ver 3 (29×29) uses interleaved blocks.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The message has 26 data bytes and is encoded using two Reed-Solomon code blocks.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Each block is a (255,233) Reed Solomon code shortened to a (35,13) code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Delsarte–Goethals–Seidel theorem illustrates an example of an application of shortened Reed–Solomon codes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In parallel to shortening, a technique known as puncturing allows omitting some of the encoded parity symbols.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The decoders described in this section use the BCH view of a codeword as a sequence of coefficients.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] They use a fixed generator polynomial known to both encoder and decoder.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Daniel Gorenstein and Neal Zierler developed a decoder that was described in a MIT Lincoln Laboratory report by Zierler in January 1960 and later in a paper in June 1961.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Gorenstein–Zierler decoder and the related work on BCH codes are described in the book *Error Correcting Codes* by W.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] As a result of the Reed–Solomon encoding procedure, *s*(*x*) is divisible by the generator polynomial $g(x)=\prod _{j=1}^{n-k}(x-\alpha ^{j}),$ where *α* is a primitive element.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Coefficient *ei* will be zero if there is no error at that power of *x*, and nonzero if there is an error.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The goal of the decoder is to find the number of errors (*ν*), the positions of the errors (*ik*), and the error values at those positions (*eik*).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] From those, *e*(*x*) can be calculated and subtracted from *r*(*x*) to get the originally sent message *s*(*x*).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The decoder starts by evaluating the polynomial as received at points $\alpha ^{1}\dots \alpha ^{n-k}$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] We call the results of that evaluation the "syndromes" *S**j*.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The advantage of looking at the syndromes is that the message polynomial drops out.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In other words, the syndromes only relate to the error and are unaffected by the actual contents of the message being transmitted.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] If the syndromes are all zero, the algorithm stops here and reports that the message was not corrupted in transit.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The syndromes give a system of *n* − *k* ≥ 2*ν* equations in 2*ν* unknowns, but that system of equations is nonlinear in the *Xk* and does not have an obvious solution.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In the variant of this algorithm where the locations of the errors are already known (when it is being used as an erasure code), this is the end.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The error locations (*Xk*) are already known by some other method (for example, in an FM transmission, the sections where the bitstream was unclear or overcome with interference are probabilistically determinable from frequency analysis).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In this scenario, up to $n-k$ errors can be corrected.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The rest of the algorithm serves to locate the errors and will require syndrome values up to $2\nu$ , instead of just the $\nu$ used thus far.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This is why twice as many error-correcting symbols need to be added as can be corrected without knowing their locations.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] There is a linear recurrence relation that gives rise to a system of linear equations.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Solving those equations identifies those error locations *Xk*.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The zeros of Λ(*x*) are the reciprocals $X_{k}^{-1}$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Let j be any integer such that $1\leq j\leq \nu$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] These summations are now equivalent to the syndrome values, which we know and can substitute in.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Recall that *j* was chosen to be any integer between 1 and *v* inclusive, and this equivalence is true for all such values.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Therefore, we have *v* linear equations, not just one.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The PGZ decoder does not determine *ν* directly but rather searches for it by trying successive values.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The decoder first assumes the largest value for a trial *ν* and sets up the linear system for that value.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] If the equations can be solved (i.e., the matrix determinant is nonzero), then that trial value is the number of errors.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] If the linear system cannot be solved, then the trial *ν* is reduced by one and the next smaller system is examined.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Use the coefficients Λ*i* found in the last step to build the error location polynomial.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The roots of the error location polynomial can be found by exhaustive search.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The error locators *Xk* are the reciprocals of those roots.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The order of coefficients of the error location polynomial can be reversed, in which case the roots of that reversed polynomial are the error locators $X_{k}$ (not their reciprocals $X_{k}^{-1}$ ).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Chien search is an efficient implementation of this step.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Once the error locators *Xk* are known, the error values can be determined.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This can be done by direct solution for *Yk* in the error equations matrix given above, or using the Forney algorithm.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Calculate *ik* by taking the log base $\alpha$ of *Xk*.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This is generally done using a precomputed lookup table.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Finally, *e*(*x*) is generated from *ik* and *eik* and then is subtracted from *r*(*x*) to get the originally sent message *s*(*x*), with errors corrected.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Consider the Reed–Solomon code defined in *GF*(929) with *α* = 3 and *t* = 4 (this is used in PDF417 barcodes) for a RS(7,3) code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The coefficients can be reversed: $R(x)=001x^{2}+821x+329,$ to produce roots 27 = 33 and 81 = 34 with positive exponents, but typically this isn't used.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The logarithm of the inverted roots corresponds to the error locations (right to left, location 0 is the last term in the codeword).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Berlekamp–Massey algorithm is an alternate iterative procedure for finding the error locator polynomial.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] During each iteration, it calculates a discrepancy based on a current instance of Λ(*x*) with an assumed number of errors *e*: $\Delta =S_{i}+\Lambda _{1}\ S_{i-1}+\cdots +\Lambda _{e}\ S_{i-e}$ and then adjusts Λ(*x*) and *e* so that a recalculated Δ would be zero.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The article Berlekamp–Massey algorithm has a detailed description of the procedure.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In the following example, *C*(*x*) is used to represent Λ(*x*).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The final value of *C* is the error locator polynomial, Λ(*x*).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Another iterative method for calculating both the error locator polynomial and the error value polynomial is based on Sugiyama's adaptation of the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The middle terms are zero due to the relationship between Λ and syndromes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] where the degree of *R* decreases as *i* increases.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] A discrete Fourier transform can be used for decoding.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] To avoid conflict with syndrome names, let *c*(*x*) = *s*(*x*) the encoded codeword.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Transform *r*(*x*) to *R*(*x*) using discrete Fourier transform.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Use $R_{1}$ through $R_{t}$ as syndromes (they're the same) and generate the error locator polynomial using the methods from any of the above decoders.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Then calculate *C*(*x*) = *R*(*x*) − *E*(*x*) and take the inverse transform (polynomial interpolation) of *C*(*x*) to produce *c*(*x*).
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Singleton bound states that the minimum distance d of a linear block code of size (n,k) is upper-bounded by *n* - *k* + 1.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The distance d was usually understood to limit the error-correction capability to ⌊(*d* - 1) / 2⌋.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The Reed–Solomon code achieves this bound with equality, and can thus correct up to ⌊(*n* - *k*) / 2⌋ errors.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] However, this error-correction bound is not exact.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 1999, Madhu Sudan and Venkatesan Guruswami at MIT published "Improved Decoding of Reed–Solomon and Algebraic-Geometry Codes" introducing an algorithm that allowed for the correction of errors beyond half the minimum distance of the code.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] It applies to Reed–Solomon codes and more generally to algebraic geometric codes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] This algorithm produces a list of codewords (it is a list-decoding algorithm) and is based on interpolation and factorization of polynomials over *GF*(2*m*) and its extensions.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 2023, coding theorists showed that Reed-Solomon codes defined over random evaluation points can achieve achieve list decoding capacity (up to *n* - *k* errors) over linear size alphabets with high probability.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] These results do not provide an algorithm for performing the decoding.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The algebraic decoding methods described above are hard-decision methods, which means that for every symbol a hard decision is made about its value.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] For example, a decoder could associate with each symbol an additional value corresponding to the channel demodulator's confidence in the correctness of the symbol.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] The advent of LDPC and turbo codes, which employ iterated soft-decision belief propagation decoding methods to achieve error-correction performance close to the theoretical limit, has spurred interest in applying soft-decision decoding to conventional algebraic codes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] In 2003, Ralf Koetter and Alexander Vardy presented a polynomial-time soft-decision algebraic list-decoding algorithm for Reed–Solomon codes, which was based upon the work by Sudan and Guruswami.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p01] Taylor published a novel soft-decision decoder.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] The decoders described in this section use the Reed Solomon original view of a codeword as a sequence of polynomial values where the polynomial is based on the message to be encoded.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] The same set of fixed values are used by the encoder and decoder, and the decoder recovers the encoding polynomial (and optionally an error locating polynomial) from the received message.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] Reed and Solomon described a theoretical decoder that corrected errors by finding the most popular message polynomial.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] The decoder only knows the set of values $a_{1}$ to $a_{n}$ and which encoding method was used to generate the codeword's sequence of values.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] The original message, the polynomial, and any errors are unknown.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] A decoding procedure could use a method like Lagrange interpolation on various subsets of n codeword values taken k at a time to repeatedly produce potential polynomials, until a sufficient number of matching polynomials are produced to reasonably eliminate any errors in the received codeword.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] Once a polynomial is determined, then any errors in the codeword can be corrected, by recalculating the corresponding codeword values.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] Unfortunately, in all but the simplest of cases, there are too many subsets, so the algorithm is impractical.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] The number of subsets is the binomial coefficient, ${\textstyle {\binom {n}{k}}={n! \over (n-k)!k!}}$ , and the number of subsets is infeasible for even modest codes.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] For a (255,249) code that can correct 3 errors, the naïve theoretical decoder would examine 359 billion subsets.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] The recovered polynomial is then used to recover (recalculate as needed) the original message.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] Errors in transmission might cause this to be received instead.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] Assume maximum number of errors: *e* = 2.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] In 2002, an improved decoder was developed by Shuhong Gao, based on the extended Euclid algorithm.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] To duplicate the polynomials generated by Berlekamp Welsh, divide *Q*(*x*) and *E*(*x*) by most significant coefficient of *E*(*x*) = 708.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] Around 2015, an improved decoder was developed.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] The decoder generates syndromes, and similar to BCH view, the key equation between the error locator polynomial and syndromes is the same, but the error locator polynomial has roots corresponding to $(1/\alpha _{i})$ , and a look up table is used to convert the roots into codeword offsets.
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] A set of n polynomials is defined: $L_{i}=L/(x-\alpha _{i})$ .
[src:information-theory/reed-solomon-error-correction-p02] A set of n values is generated $u_{i}=L_{i}(\alpha _{i})$ .
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] In information theory, the **Shannon–Hartley theorem** tells the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted over a communications channel of a specified bandwidth in the presence of noise.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] It is an application of the noisy-channel coding theorem to the archetypal case of a continuous-time analog communications channel subject to Gaussian noise.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] The law is named after Claude Shannon and Ralph Hartley.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] During the late 1920s, Harry Nyquist and Ralph Hartley developed a handful of fundamental ideas related to the transmission of information, particularly in the context of the telegraph as a communications system.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] At the time, these concepts were powerful breakthroughs individually, but they were not part of a comprehensive theory.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] In the 1940s, Claude Shannon developed the concept of channel capacity, based in part on the ideas of Nyquist and Hartley, and then formulated a complete theory of information and its transmission.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] In 1927, Nyquist determined that the number of independent pulses that could be put through a telegraph channel per unit time is limited to twice the one-sided bandwidth of the channel.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] where $f_{p}$ is the pulse frequency (in pulses per second) and B is the one-sided bandwidth (in hertz).
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] The quantity $2B$ later came to be called the *Nyquist rate*, and transmitting at the limiting pulse rate of $2B$ pulses per second as *signalling at the Nyquist rate*.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Nyquist published his results in 1928 as part of his paper "Certain topics in Telegraph Transmission Theory".
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] During 1928, Hartley formulated a way to quantify information and its line rate (also known as data signalling rate *R* bits per second).
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] This method, later known as Hartley's law, became an important precursor for Shannon's more sophisticated notion of channel capacity.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Hartley argued that the maximum number of distinguishable pulse levels that can be transmitted and received reliably over a communications channel is limited by the dynamic range of the signal amplitude and the precision with which the receiver can distinguish amplitude levels.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] where $f_{p}$ is the pulse rate, also known as the symbol rate, in symbols/second or baud.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Hartley then combined the above quantification with Nyquist's observation that the number of independent pulses that could be put through a channel of one-sided bandwidth B hertz was $2B$ pulses per second, to arrive at his quantitative measure for achievable line rate.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Hartley's law is sometimes quoted as just a proportionality between the analog bandwidth, B , in Hertz and what today is called the digital bandwidth, R , in bit/s.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] The concept of an error-free capacity awaited Claude Shannon, who built on Hartley's observations about a logarithmic measure of information and Nyquist's observations about the effect of bandwidth limitations.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Hartley's rate result can be viewed as the capacity of an errorless *M*-ary channel of $2B$ symbols per second.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] But such an errorless channel is an idealization, and if M is chosen small enough to make the noisy channel nearly errorless, the result is necessarily less than the Shannon capacity of the noisy channel of bandwidth B , which is the Hartley–Shannon result that followed later.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Claude Shannon's development of information theory during World War II provided the next big step in understanding how much information could be reliably communicated through noisy channels.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Building on Hartley's foundation, Shannon's noisy channel coding theorem (1948) describes the maximum possible efficiency of error-correcting methods versus levels of noise interference and data corruption.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] The proof of the theorem shows that a randomly constructed error-correcting code is essentially as good as the best possible code; the theorem is proved through the statistics of such random codes.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] there exists a coding technique which allows the probability of error at the receiver to be made arbitrarily small.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] This means that theoretically, it is possible to transmit information nearly without error up to nearly a limit of C bits per second.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] the probability of error at the receiver increases without bound as the rate is increased, so no useful information can be transmitted beyond the channel capacity.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] The theorem does not address the rare situation in which rate and capacity are equal.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] The Shannon–Hartley theorem establishes what that channel capacity is for a finite-bandwidth continuous-time channel subject to Gaussian noise.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] If there were such a thing as a noise-free analog channel, one could transmit unlimited amounts of error-free data over it per unit of time (Note that an infinite-bandwidth analog channel could not transmit unlimited amounts of error-free data absent infinite signal power).
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Real channels, however, are subject to limitations imposed by both finite bandwidth and nonzero noise.
[src:information-theory/shannon-hartley-theorem] Bandwidth and noise affect the rate at which information can be transmitted over an analog channel.
